1
00:01:22,982 --> 00:01:24,347
BROADCASTER:
<i>Here comes the pitch.</i>

2
00:01:24,551 --> 00:01:25,518
[BALL THUDS]

3
00:01:25,718 --> 00:01:27,117
<i>Strike three. He struck him out.</i>

4
00:01:27,320 --> 00:01:28,787
[CROWD CHEERING]

5
00:01:39,866 --> 00:01:41,265
[CHATTERING]

6
00:01:41,468 --> 00:01:44,699
Oh, okay. Tommy Dorsey or Glenn Miller?

7
00:01:44,904 --> 00:01:46,769
- Tommy Dorsey.
LYLE: Uh, why?

8
00:01:46,973 --> 00:01:48,531
- My Frankie.
- Ah.

9
00:01:48,741 --> 00:01:50,572
Heh, that skinny little Italian cat?

10
00:01:50,777 --> 00:01:53,974
- No, hell, no.
LYLE: Come on. How about this one, huh?

11
00:01:54,180 --> 00:01:55,442
What's that?

12
00:01:55,648 --> 00:01:58,617
[JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING
ON RECORD PLAYER]

13
00:02:00,286 --> 00:02:03,255
[WOMAN SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

14
00:02:04,991 --> 00:02:06,754
I need your help on Sunday.

15
00:02:06,960 --> 00:02:10,555
Uh, yeah, sure. No problem.
Oh, hey.

16
00:02:10,763 --> 00:02:12,822
I got the promotion.
Can you believe that?

17
00:02:13,032 --> 00:02:14,659
Five years and I'm finally doing it.

18
00:02:14,868 --> 00:02:16,130
That looks so good.

19
00:02:16,336 --> 00:02:18,327
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

20
00:02:18,538 --> 00:02:21,507
LYLE: There's only one guy on your team.
Is it Joe DiMaggio or Ted Williams?

21
00:02:21,708 --> 00:02:23,835
MAN: Yankee Clipper.
Sweetest swing in the game.

22
00:02:24,043 --> 00:02:25,067
LYLE:
How about this one:

23
00:02:25,278 --> 00:02:27,405
- Bette Davis or Rita Hayworth?
- Ooh!

24
00:02:27,614 --> 00:02:30,674
- Ha-ha-ha. I'll take them both.
- In your dreams.

25
00:02:30,884 --> 00:02:32,181
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

26
00:02:32,385 --> 00:02:34,751
Come and get it. Hot dog, hamburger.

27
00:02:34,954 --> 00:02:37,388
And Benny's hot-and-spicy sausages.

28
00:02:37,590 --> 00:02:40,491
[LYLE PLAYING JAZZ MUSIC
ON SAXOPHONE]

29
00:02:43,863 --> 00:02:45,262
KAZ:
Lane, get your brother.

30
00:02:45,465 --> 00:02:46,523
[EMI SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

31
00:02:46,733 --> 00:02:48,633
LANE: Hey, Lyle!
- What do you want?

32
00:02:48,835 --> 00:02:50,496
Okay.

33
00:03:00,647 --> 00:03:02,979
LYLE [IN VOICE-OVER]: <i>Jazz and baseball.</i>
- Faster.

34
00:03:03,183 --> 00:03:04,912
LYLE:
<i>The sax I picked up on my own.</i>

35
00:03:05,818 --> 00:03:09,845
<i>The baseball, that was my dad.</i>
<i>Taught me everything I know about it.</i>

36
00:03:10,056 --> 00:03:13,048
<i>And it got me an athletic scholarship</i>
<i>to San Francisco State.</i>

37
00:03:13,960 --> 00:03:17,987
<i>My older brother Lane went straight from</i>
<i>high school to working to help the family...</i>

38
00:03:18,198 --> 00:03:21,224
<i>...so I'm gonna be the first</i>
<i>to go to college.</i>

39
00:03:21,935 --> 00:03:23,459
<i>Jazz and baseball.</i>

40
00:03:31,811 --> 00:03:33,938
ROOSEVELT [ON RADIO]:
<i>Yesterday...</i>

41
00:03:34,514 --> 00:03:39,474
<i>...December 7th, 1941...</i>

42
00:03:40,520 --> 00:03:45,287
...a date which will live in infamy...

43
00:03:45,491 --> 00:03:48,119
...the United States of America...

44
00:03:48,328 --> 00:03:51,695
<i>...was suddenly</i>
<i>and deliberately attacked...</i>

45
00:03:51,898 --> 00:03:57,530
<i>...by naval and air forces</i>
<i>of the Empire of Japan.</i>

46
00:03:57,737 --> 00:04:01,195
<i>The United States was at peace</i>
<i>with that nation...</i>

47
00:04:02,609 --> 00:04:07,308
<i>...and at the solicitation of Japan...</i>

48
00:04:07,513 --> 00:04:13,975
<i>...was still in conversation</i>
<i>with its government and its emperor...</i>

49
00:04:14,187 --> 00:04:17,782
<i>...looking toward the maintenance</i>
<i>of peace in the Pacific.</i>

50
00:04:19,626 --> 00:04:22,595
[ROOSEVELT SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
ON RADIO]

51
00:04:36,709 --> 00:04:39,143
LYLE:
<i>We were given 10 days' notice.</i>

52
00:04:39,345 --> 00:04:42,473
<i>Ten days to close the family business...</i>

53
00:04:42,682 --> 00:04:47,381
<i>...to sell our furniture,</i>
<i>to clear everything from our home.</i>

54
00:04:47,987 --> 00:04:50,547
<i>We gave our dog to the neighbors.</i>

55
00:04:51,024 --> 00:04:53,959
<i>I smashed my records</i>
<i>and left them there.</i>

56
00:05:10,743 --> 00:05:14,042
<i>We were only allowed to bring</i>
<i>what we could carry with us.</i>

57
00:05:15,048 --> 00:05:17,915
<i>First we were held</i>
<i>at the Santa Anita racetrack...</i>

58
00:05:18,117 --> 00:05:20,108
<i>...living in a horse stall.</i>

59
00:05:21,621 --> 00:05:23,111
<i>Then we were taken further away.</i>

60
00:05:25,825 --> 00:05:28,157
<i>Everything we had known was gone.</i>

61
00:05:28,361 --> 00:05:31,797
ROOSEVELT [ON RADIO]:
<i>--determination of our people.</i>

62
00:05:31,998 --> 00:05:36,196
<i>We will gain the inevitable triumph...</i>

63
00:05:36,402 --> 00:05:39,098
<i>...so help us God.</i>

64
00:05:48,715 --> 00:05:50,114
[CAR APPROACHING]

65
00:05:50,316 --> 00:05:53,183
[MAN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY
AND THEN BABY CRYING]

66
00:05:53,453 --> 00:05:56,786
[OFFICER SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
OVER LOUDSPEAKER]

67
00:06:01,227 --> 00:06:03,092
[CHATTERING]

68
00:06:11,771 --> 00:06:13,739
[WHISTLE BLOWING]

69
00:06:24,450 --> 00:06:26,418
[JEEP HORN HONKING]

70
00:06:30,356 --> 00:06:32,654
OFFICER [ON LOUDSPEAKER]: <i>Prisoner...</i>
MAN: Identification?

71
00:06:32,859 --> 00:06:33,917
<i>...step away from the fence.</i>

72
00:06:34,127 --> 00:06:36,391
SOLDIER [SHOUTING]:
Get on with it, now.

73
00:06:36,596 --> 00:06:38,587
Keep away from the damn fence!

74
00:06:38,798 --> 00:06:41,665
OFFICER [ON LOUDSPEAKER]:
<i>Follow all instructions and keep calm.</i>

75
00:06:42,468 --> 00:06:44,493
SOLDIER:
Okay, keep the line moving.

76
00:06:44,704 --> 00:06:48,663
Go to the center circle.
Find your belongings. Stand in line.

77
00:06:48,875 --> 00:06:51,309
Once again, those of you
exiting these vehicles...

78
00:06:51,511 --> 00:06:54,344
...or anyone by the center circle...

79
00:06:54,547 --> 00:06:58,005
...keep the line moving.
Head of the line's right there.

80
00:06:59,685 --> 00:07:02,210
If you're not sure what line
you're supposed to be in...

81
00:07:02,422 --> 00:07:05,880
...find a soldier or an officer
that is near to you and ask them.

82
00:07:06,092 --> 00:07:08,822
Once again, once you exit this vehicle...

83
00:07:09,028 --> 00:07:11,758
...go to the center circle
to get your belongings quickly.

84
00:07:11,964 --> 00:07:13,795
Okay. Let's go.

85
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,025
BILLY:
If you're not sure, ask one of the soldiers.

86
00:07:16,235 --> 00:07:18,863
They will tell what line you should be in.

87
00:07:19,071 --> 00:07:21,938
Keep it moving. All right,
right here, just keep it moving.

88
00:07:22,141 --> 00:07:25,474
She can get her own things.
Move on. Move on.

89
00:07:26,779 --> 00:07:28,508
BILLY:
Once you got your bag, just move on.

90
00:07:29,782 --> 00:07:33,843
Hey. You, in the gray cap.
You understand English?

91
00:07:34,320 --> 00:07:35,878
Get up, get back in line.

92
00:07:36,088 --> 00:07:37,612
Go, go, go. Go. Go.

93
00:07:37,824 --> 00:07:40,793
- She's my mother.
- I'm okay. Go, go.

94
00:07:44,130 --> 00:07:47,099
[OFFICER SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
ON LOUDSPEAKER]

95
00:07:59,045 --> 00:08:01,013
[CHATTERING]

96
00:08:01,214 --> 00:08:03,580
BILLY: Find your belongings
and then get in line.

97
00:08:09,021 --> 00:08:12,684
Once again,
those of you exiting these vehicles...

98
00:08:52,732 --> 00:08:55,292
KAZ: How are you?
- I'm fine.

99
00:08:55,501 --> 00:08:57,059
Okay.

100
00:08:57,770 --> 00:09:01,729
[OFFICER SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
ON LOUDSPEAKER]

101
00:09:15,354 --> 00:09:18,255
Can we have everyone's attention?

102
00:09:19,525 --> 00:09:22,016
KAZ:
Inspection is in a few minutes.

103
00:09:22,662 --> 00:09:24,960
Not enough time to go outside.

104
00:09:25,164 --> 00:09:27,325
We change here.

105
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:30,434
Men and boys, come to this side.

106
00:09:30,636 --> 00:09:34,231
And will please all the women and girls
come to this side.

107
00:09:34,440 --> 00:09:36,271
KAZ:
Okay.

108
00:10:05,037 --> 00:10:06,436
[DOOR OPENS]

109
00:10:06,639 --> 00:10:10,541
Block 41, Barracks 11, bed check.
Everybody step to your cots.

110
00:10:10,743 --> 00:10:12,233
[WOMEN GASPING]

111
00:10:13,179 --> 00:10:15,147
[CHATTERING]

112
00:10:21,487 --> 00:10:24,979
Is that one of those trick pictures
like they have at carnivals or...?

113
00:10:25,191 --> 00:10:28,354
LANE:
No, my dad played semipro ball.

114
00:10:28,561 --> 00:10:31,496
See, Ruth, Gehrig, Jimmie Foxx,
they're on a barnstorming team.

115
00:10:31,697 --> 00:10:33,494
They play on my dad's all-star team.

116
00:10:33,699 --> 00:10:35,326
See?

117
00:10:35,835 --> 00:10:38,804
Well, this guy right here,
he's about as close as you can get...

118
00:10:39,005 --> 00:10:42,907
...without actually being a real Yankee.
He's in their farm system, Class A ball.

119
00:10:43,109 --> 00:10:45,737
Line up. If you're not there
when your name is called...

120
00:10:45,945 --> 00:10:48,140
...you will be reported as missing curfew.

121
00:10:48,347 --> 00:10:50,008
MACK:
Nomura.

122
00:10:50,216 --> 00:10:55,176
Emyko, Kazuo, Lane and Lyle Nomura.

123
00:10:55,388 --> 00:10:57,015
KAZ:
I am Kazuo.

124
00:10:57,223 --> 00:11:01,057
My wife, my sons.

125
00:11:01,260 --> 00:11:02,818
MAN:
Good evening.

126
00:11:03,029 --> 00:11:07,159
My name is Walter Watson,
and I'm the director of this camp.

127
00:11:08,267 --> 00:11:11,395
WATSON: The government has created
this camp with your well-being in mind.

128
00:11:11,604 --> 00:11:14,232
Every effort has been made here
to make your transition...

129
00:11:14,440 --> 00:11:15,839
...as smooth as possible.

130
00:11:16,042 --> 00:11:18,340
You'll have an opportunity to live
and work here...

131
00:11:18,544 --> 00:11:23,174
...and establish constructive lives
as close to those that you previously had.

132
00:11:24,150 --> 00:11:27,847
As for me personally, I look forward to
working with each and every one of you...

133
00:11:28,054 --> 00:11:31,114
...and I wish to bid you all
a very good first night.

134
00:12:30,049 --> 00:12:31,641
[CROWD CHEERING]

135
00:12:31,851 --> 00:12:34,877
ANNOUNCER:
Single-A minor-league pro ball.

136
00:12:36,322 --> 00:12:37,516
Coming to the plate...

137
00:12:37,723 --> 00:12:39,088
...Bees catcher Billy Burrell.

138
00:12:40,126 --> 00:12:42,424
ANNOUNCER: Billy's the heart and soul
of his team's game.

139
00:12:44,063 --> 00:12:45,792
WOMAN:
All right, hit it out of the park!

140
00:12:46,398 --> 00:12:48,366
ANNOUNCER:
If you ask me, Billy is still showing...

141
00:12:48,567 --> 00:12:51,127
...why he was once considered
a major-league prospect.

142
00:12:53,472 --> 00:12:55,099
[CROWD ROARS]

143
00:12:56,542 --> 00:12:59,010
My, oh, my, look at it fly.

144
00:13:00,279 --> 00:13:02,144
ANNOUNCER:
Billy caught all of that one.

145
00:13:02,348 --> 00:13:04,441
That's a two-run shot.

146
00:13:06,118 --> 00:13:08,882
That's the game winner, Billy Burrell!

147
00:13:10,022 --> 00:13:12,820
ANNOUNCER:
Your Abraham Bees pull it out, 6 to 5.

148
00:13:13,025 --> 00:13:14,652
JOE:
He's having a heck of a season.

149
00:13:14,860 --> 00:13:16,487
- Ha-ha-ha.
- His best in years.

150
00:13:16,695 --> 00:13:19,892
The last time he had a start like this
was back in Triple-A.

151
00:13:20,132 --> 00:13:23,158
Don Lemon himself came out
to take a look at him.

152
00:13:23,369 --> 00:13:25,667
We really thought we were gonna get
called up that year.

153
00:13:25,871 --> 00:13:27,429
JOE:
Hmm.

154
00:13:27,973 --> 00:13:30,999
ANNOUNCER: Billy's son, Billy Jr.,
played with the Bees briefly...

155
00:13:31,210 --> 00:13:33,144
...before he shipped out to the Pacific.

156
00:13:33,345 --> 00:13:36,371
Father and son, both doing their duty
for their country.

157
00:13:38,317 --> 00:13:40,046
[CONVERSING INDISTINCTLY]

158
00:13:43,522 --> 00:13:45,012
[HAMMERING]

159
00:13:47,359 --> 00:13:50,328
[JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING
ON SAXOPHONE]

160
00:14:01,307 --> 00:14:03,275
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

161
00:14:11,750 --> 00:14:14,514
LYLE:
Hey, I can play here if I want to, okay?

162
00:14:15,154 --> 00:14:16,348
It's a free country.

163
00:14:16,822 --> 00:14:18,813
Free country, huh?

164
00:14:19,024 --> 00:14:21,959
If it's a free country,
let me see you take that horn...

165
00:14:22,161 --> 00:14:24,629
...and go on the other side
of that fence and play.

166
00:14:26,532 --> 00:14:28,432
Get out of here.

167
00:14:29,134 --> 00:14:31,364
- What is that over there?
- It's nothing for you.

168
00:14:31,570 --> 00:14:33,037
Go play someplace else.

169
00:14:33,239 --> 00:14:35,799
What do you got back there, old man?

170
00:14:36,008 --> 00:14:38,135
LYLE: You making something
with those peaches?

171
00:14:38,344 --> 00:14:39,504
Is that booze?

172
00:14:39,712 --> 00:14:40,679
[ALARM WAILING]

173
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:43,314
MAN [ON LOUDSPEAKER]:
<i>All residents must be in their barracks.</i>

174
00:14:43,515 --> 00:14:46,279
<i>All residents must remain</i>
<i>in their barracks.</i>

175
00:14:46,485 --> 00:14:48,612
<i>No one is allowed out of the barracks.</i>

176
00:14:48,821 --> 00:14:51,654
BILLY: Block 41, Barracks 11.
Name: Nomura, Lyle.

177
00:14:51,857 --> 00:14:54,291
Area around this barracks,
then perimeter search.

178
00:14:54,493 --> 00:14:56,927
BILLY: We don't find him,
we'll do barracks-to-barracks.

179
00:14:57,129 --> 00:14:59,962
NORRIS: We found him
out near the northeast firebreaks.

180
00:15:00,165 --> 00:15:02,156
- He's drunk.
NORRIS: He was lying on the ground.

181
00:15:02,368 --> 00:15:04,063
- Smart-ass said he got lost.
BILLY: Phew.

182
00:15:04,270 --> 00:15:07,501
Smells sweet.
You make some kind of home-brew?

183
00:15:09,174 --> 00:15:11,836
You make the booze,
or did somebody bring it in?

184
00:15:13,078 --> 00:15:16,138
Did you make it,
or did somebody bring it into the camp?

185
00:15:16,348 --> 00:15:19,784
BILLY:
Where--? Son of a bitch!

186
00:15:21,020 --> 00:15:22,851
WATSON:
Who called lockdown?

187
00:15:23,489 --> 00:15:25,980
Prisoner was missing.
He wasn't in his barracks.

188
00:15:26,225 --> 00:15:28,819
You are not authorized to call lockdown.

189
00:15:29,028 --> 00:15:31,997
- I'm putting him in the stockade.
- He's my son.

190
00:15:44,944 --> 00:15:46,434
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

191
00:16:00,259 --> 00:16:03,057
KAZ:
Everybody, listen.

192
00:16:03,796 --> 00:16:07,061
We have to do what we can
to make a new home...

193
00:16:07,266 --> 00:16:08,790
...each one of us.

194
00:16:09,568 --> 00:16:12,002
My father has spoken
to Director Watson...

195
00:16:12,204 --> 00:16:15,662
...and he said we're allowed
to make improvements on our barracks.

196
00:16:15,874 --> 00:16:18,866
Too many of us have gotten sick.

197
00:16:19,445 --> 00:16:21,811
We can patch the holes, uh...

198
00:16:22,014 --> 00:16:26,007
...make curtains, do whatever we can
to stop the wind and dust from coming in.

199
00:16:26,685 --> 00:16:29,051
There are over 8000 of us here.

200
00:16:30,155 --> 00:16:32,214
LANE:
We have the skills we can use.

201
00:16:34,126 --> 00:16:35,923
Now, the government won't help...

202
00:16:36,128 --> 00:16:39,427
<i>...but they will allow us</i>
<i>to use mail-order catalogs...</i>

203
00:16:39,631 --> 00:16:43,123
<i>...and to go outside</i>
<i>into town for supplies.</i>

204
00:16:43,335 --> 00:16:46,099
<i>We have to pay our own way,</i>
<i>but if everyone contributes...</i>

205
00:16:47,373 --> 00:16:49,364
<i>...then like my father said:</i>

206
00:16:49,575 --> 00:16:53,238
<i>"Out of necessity,</i>
<i>we can make a new home for ourselves."</i>

207
00:16:53,445 --> 00:16:55,174
[CHATTERING]

208
00:17:08,794 --> 00:17:13,390
ED: Says here she's a pretty nice sort
of person when she lets her hair down. Huh.

209
00:17:14,600 --> 00:17:17,125
Did you know Rita Hayworth
was actually a Mexican?

210
00:17:19,405 --> 00:17:20,599
Hey, Billy.

211
00:17:21,340 --> 00:17:22,739
Ed.

212
00:17:27,780 --> 00:17:31,739
Camp okayed the Japs to come in,
order some supplies directly.

213
00:17:32,751 --> 00:17:34,981
Hi, I'm Kaz.

214
00:17:35,187 --> 00:17:37,587
- My son Lane.
- Hi.

215
00:17:39,625 --> 00:17:41,684
Do you have in stock?

216
00:17:44,663 --> 00:17:48,622
"Fertilizer, watermelon seeds,
strawberry plants."

217
00:17:48,834 --> 00:17:50,802
What's this, uh...?

218
00:17:51,036 --> 00:17:53,163
JOE: Ginger something?
- Uh, that's gingham.

219
00:17:53,372 --> 00:17:56,000
JOE: The material?
- Yeah, my mom wants it to make curtains.

220
00:17:56,642 --> 00:17:58,200
How you gonna pay for all this?

221
00:17:59,011 --> 00:18:00,569
- Cash.
ED: Ha.

222
00:18:00,779 --> 00:18:03,339
Now we're giving
these people cash too?

223
00:18:03,549 --> 00:18:05,608
ED:
Sure, bring them here.

224
00:18:05,818 --> 00:18:08,082
We'll take care of them, we'll feed them.

225
00:18:08,287 --> 00:18:12,018
We'll house them, and you know what?
While we're at it...

226
00:18:12,224 --> 00:18:15,352
...why don't we give them some extra cash,
just to go along with it?

227
00:18:17,763 --> 00:18:20,254
No one is giving us money.

228
00:18:20,766 --> 00:18:23,894
We were afraid banks
would take our savings...

229
00:18:24,103 --> 00:18:25,730
...so we brought money here.

230
00:18:25,938 --> 00:18:28,065
- Bullshit.
- Leave them alone, Ed.

231
00:18:28,273 --> 00:18:30,798
You're not gonna win the war in here.

232
00:18:31,009 --> 00:18:33,136
Let me see what I got in stock.

233
00:18:33,345 --> 00:18:35,939
As long as you can make a buck out of it.

234
00:18:38,817 --> 00:18:40,182
[LANE SIGHS]

235
00:18:41,820 --> 00:18:43,685
- It's okay.
- Yeah.

236
00:18:52,998 --> 00:18:55,489
Katie got a letter from your boy Jackie.

237
00:18:55,701 --> 00:18:56,929
Hmm.

238
00:18:57,136 --> 00:18:59,366
Yeah, they're shipping him out
to the Solomons...

239
00:18:59,571 --> 00:19:01,505
...not far from where your son is.

240
00:19:01,707 --> 00:19:04,403
We said a prayer for him
last night at dinner.

241
00:19:04,877 --> 00:19:06,708
I appreciate that, Billy.

242
00:19:09,715 --> 00:19:12,206
Yeah, we got most of it here...

243
00:19:12,417 --> 00:19:14,544
...but those curtains?
Gonna have to order.

244
00:19:15,053 --> 00:19:16,315
- Thank you.
- Thanks.

245
00:19:16,522 --> 00:19:17,580
[ED SCOFFS]

246
00:19:17,789 --> 00:19:19,689
Gingham curtains?

247
00:19:22,995 --> 00:19:24,622
MAN:
How can we be held?

248
00:19:24,830 --> 00:19:29,199
How can we be held without being charged
with breaking any laws?

249
00:19:29,701 --> 00:19:31,498
What happened to the Constitution?

250
00:19:31,703 --> 00:19:34,501
Where are all the Germans?
What about the Italians?

251
00:19:35,507 --> 00:19:37,702
MAN:
Demand answers.

252
00:19:37,910 --> 00:19:41,311
Join us. Come on.

253
00:19:41,747 --> 00:19:44,272
Demand answers.

254
00:19:45,717 --> 00:19:48,811
You're afraid. You're all afraid.

255
00:20:03,202 --> 00:20:05,067
Where do you think they're taking them?

256
00:20:05,270 --> 00:20:07,204
Nobody knows.

257
00:20:07,673 --> 00:20:10,141
They don't know where they're going
or for how long.

258
00:20:11,510 --> 00:20:14,604
NORI:
They got a special camp for these guys.

259
00:20:15,147 --> 00:20:18,207
They put all the bad apples in one place...

260
00:20:18,917 --> 00:20:22,546
...and make apple cider out of them.

261
00:20:23,488 --> 00:20:24,978
Come on. Let's go.

262
00:20:30,229 --> 00:20:31,423
NORI:
Now, listen.

263
00:20:32,064 --> 00:20:34,931
Where there are people,
there's gonna be drinking and gambling.

264
00:20:35,133 --> 00:20:38,364
Where there's drinking and gambling,
there's money to be made.

265
00:20:38,570 --> 00:20:39,764
You that good of a gambler?

266
00:20:39,972 --> 00:20:42,372
There's no such thing as a good gambler.

267
00:20:42,574 --> 00:20:46,340
Hey, I haven't risked a nickel in 25 years.

268
00:20:46,545 --> 00:20:50,606
The only way to win in gambling
is to be the house, the bank...

269
00:20:50,816 --> 00:20:52,181
...to run the games.

270
00:20:52,384 --> 00:20:54,147
[LYLE PLAYING SAXOPHONE]

271
00:20:55,320 --> 00:20:58,346
NORI: <i>That way, I don't give a damn</i>
<i>who wins or loses.</i>

272
00:20:58,857 --> 00:21:02,088
<i>Just give me a little piece of the play.</i>

273
00:21:03,195 --> 00:21:05,686
<i>People wanna drink,</i>
<i>I'll make it for nothing...</i>

274
00:21:05,897 --> 00:21:07,558
<i>...and sell it to them for a buck.</i>

275
00:21:07,766 --> 00:21:09,597
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

276
00:21:09,801 --> 00:21:11,530
<i>Hey, it's business.</i>

277
00:21:29,221 --> 00:21:31,052
Hurry up.

278
00:21:31,256 --> 00:21:33,554
Hey, what does he wanna talk about?

279
00:21:33,759 --> 00:21:34,817
[LANE SCOFFING]

280
00:21:35,027 --> 00:21:36,688
- I don't know.
- Yes, you do.

281
00:21:36,895 --> 00:21:38,590
All right, okay. Maybe I do.

282
00:21:38,797 --> 00:21:41,595
Let's go, let's go.
Just be a big boy.

283
00:21:42,634 --> 00:21:44,295
Okay.

284
00:21:55,147 --> 00:21:57,274
LYLE:
You wanted to talk to me?

285
00:22:03,088 --> 00:22:08,082
When I was a young boy,
I came to America.

286
00:22:08,727 --> 00:22:11,059
I could not speak English.

287
00:22:11,263 --> 00:22:13,754
KAZ:
Kids made fun of me.

288
00:22:14,499 --> 00:22:18,595
One day, I found a game.

289
00:22:19,905 --> 00:22:22,669
- Baseball.
- Baseball. Yeah.

290
00:22:26,144 --> 00:22:28,612
KAZ:
And I became good.

291
00:22:29,314 --> 00:22:33,375
I became so good, no one could deny it.

292
00:22:33,819 --> 00:22:38,381
And the kids stopped making fun of me.

293
00:22:56,074 --> 00:22:58,634
I want to make a league here...

294
00:22:59,277 --> 00:23:02,269
...just like we had at home.

295
00:23:07,652 --> 00:23:11,816
You remember the first time
you put a ball in my hand? I was 5.

296
00:23:12,824 --> 00:23:18,285
You told me about Babe Ruth
and Lou Gehrig. Lefty Grove.

297
00:23:18,897 --> 00:23:21,297
You made me believe
that I could be Babe Ruth.

298
00:23:22,734 --> 00:23:27,262
That that was possible,
that I could try to be like him.

299
00:23:28,039 --> 00:23:30,234
But you know what, Dad?

300
00:23:31,109 --> 00:23:32,474
It's not true.

301
00:23:55,567 --> 00:23:58,536
[MUSIC PLAYING ON PIANO
AND GIRLS SINGING]

302
00:24:21,359 --> 00:24:25,318
[LYLE PLAYING SAXOPHONE
AND THEN GIRLS GIGGLING]

303
00:24:25,630 --> 00:24:27,757
Girls. You making fun of us?

304
00:24:28,400 --> 00:24:29,526
[HONKING]

305
00:24:30,602 --> 00:24:31,967
Shh.

306
00:24:32,170 --> 00:24:33,797
I don't think that's very funny.

307
00:24:34,706 --> 00:24:38,107
I have the room here from 4:30.
Jazz-band auditions.

308
00:24:38,310 --> 00:24:42,178
Well, we're not done here yet,
so you'll just have to wait, okay?

309
00:24:42,914 --> 00:24:44,472
All right, girls, focus.

310
00:24:44,683 --> 00:24:47,243
KATIE:
Eyes front. Let's try it again, okay?

311
00:24:47,452 --> 00:24:51,980
And one, two, three. One, two, three.

312
00:24:52,190 --> 00:24:55,489
[MUSIC PLAYING ON PIANO
AND GIRLS SINGING]

313
00:25:04,970 --> 00:25:06,938
[COUNTRY MUSIC PLAYING]

314
00:25:12,511 --> 00:25:13,944
BILLY:
Jesus.

315
00:25:15,313 --> 00:25:16,280
Hollister.

316
00:25:16,481 --> 00:25:18,949
That kid Don Lemon brought up
to the Yankees?

317
00:25:19,150 --> 00:25:20,777
Did he make the news in New York?

318
00:25:20,986 --> 00:25:23,011
You know, he reminded me of Billy Jr.

319
00:25:23,688 --> 00:25:27,021
I thought he really had a chance.
I taught him things I believe.

320
00:25:27,225 --> 00:25:29,819
He never even got an at bat.

321
00:25:32,597 --> 00:25:34,861
Can you imagine that?
You spend your whole life...

322
00:25:35,066 --> 00:25:37,899
...dreaming of making it there,
then get called into the Army.

323
00:25:38,103 --> 00:25:40,298
Why couldn't they at least
let him have one?

324
00:25:40,505 --> 00:25:42,769
Just one stinking big-league at bat?

325
00:25:42,974 --> 00:25:45,602
Wasn't any sugar left.
Must have used it all up.

326
00:25:45,810 --> 00:25:47,903
SHIRLEY:
Billy, take a look at this lineup now.

327
00:25:48,113 --> 00:25:51,947
The great New York Yankees.
No DiMaggio, no Bill Dickey.

328
00:25:52,150 --> 00:25:54,209
- The starters are all gone.
- Yeah.

329
00:25:54,419 --> 00:25:55,647
SHIRLEY:
In another few months...

330
00:25:55,854 --> 00:25:58,823
...the war's gonna take everybody
between the ages of 18 and 35.

331
00:26:01,393 --> 00:26:03,861
We're gonna have another chance.

332
00:26:04,429 --> 00:26:05,396
I'm too damn old.

333
00:26:05,597 --> 00:26:07,690
SHIRLEY:
No, no, not with the way things are now.

334
00:26:07,899 --> 00:26:09,662
The war's changing everything.

335
00:26:10,402 --> 00:26:13,132
We've gotta get Don Lemon
here in that fancy car of his...

336
00:26:13,338 --> 00:26:14,805
...and take another look at you.

337
00:26:15,006 --> 00:26:16,268
KATIE:
Big leagues, New York City?

338
00:26:16,474 --> 00:26:19,272
I haven't heard you talk like this
since I was a little girl.

339
00:26:19,477 --> 00:26:21,911
- Your mother's dreaming, sweetie.
SHIRLEY: Mm-mm.

340
00:26:22,480 --> 00:26:23,742
[SHIRLEY CHUCKLES]

341
00:26:23,982 --> 00:26:25,950
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

342
00:26:26,318 --> 00:26:30,448
MAN 1: All right, Lane. Come on. Batter up.
MAN 2: One time, right down the middle.

343
00:26:30,655 --> 00:26:32,179
[MEN CHEERING]

344
00:26:33,024 --> 00:26:35,720
MAN 1: Come on.
MAN 2: You too, baby. One more, one more.

345
00:26:35,927 --> 00:26:37,986
LYLE: <i>My brother never had any interest</i>
<i>in baseball.</i>

346
00:26:38,196 --> 00:26:40,528
<i>I mean, he could barely</i>
<i>even throw a ball.</i>

347
00:26:40,732 --> 00:26:41,960
<i>But it was him, not me...</i>

348
00:26:42,167 --> 00:26:44,533
<i>...who helped my father</i>
<i>get guys organized and start playing.</i>

349
00:26:44,736 --> 00:26:45,703
[CHATTERING]

350
00:26:45,904 --> 00:26:47,531
<i>And after that, it just...</i>

351
00:26:47,739 --> 00:26:50,970
<i>It was never the same between me</i>
<i>and my father and brother.</i>

352
00:26:52,711 --> 00:26:55,680
[BAMBINO PLAYING UKULELE
AND SINGING]

353
00:26:58,750 --> 00:27:00,240
Wait.

354
00:27:03,088 --> 00:27:04,715
MAN 1:
Let's go, come on!

355
00:27:04,923 --> 00:27:07,790
Two teams.
Pick which one you want to be on.

356
00:27:07,993 --> 00:27:09,017
[BAMBINO LAUGHS]

357
00:27:09,227 --> 00:27:10,717
- Home-run champ, bro.
KAZ: What?

358
00:27:10,929 --> 00:27:13,591
- <i>Da kine</i> Hawaiian league.
- Shortstop, Fresno Tigers.

359
00:27:13,798 --> 00:27:15,527
Let's go, let's go.

360
00:27:15,734 --> 00:27:17,725
[MEN CHEERING]

361
00:27:23,508 --> 00:27:24,839
MAN 1: Come on.
MAN 2: Go, go, go.

362
00:27:25,043 --> 00:27:27,739
MAN 2:
In the middle! We got him!

363
00:27:31,249 --> 00:27:32,682
Thank you, son.

364
00:27:34,653 --> 00:27:37,747
Give me something right here.
Give me something. Give me something.

365
00:27:39,824 --> 00:27:41,155
MAN 2:
Come on, Lane.

366
00:27:42,560 --> 00:27:44,528
[MEN LAUGHING AND CHEERING]

367
00:27:45,530 --> 00:27:47,521
- Foul, it's a foul ball.
BAMBINO: Oh, yeah.

368
00:27:47,732 --> 00:27:51,190
- Home run all the way, little brother.
LANE: It's a foul ball. Foul ball.

369
00:27:51,403 --> 00:27:53,701
BAMBINO: Fair ball. Fair ball.
LANE: Foul ball.

370
00:27:53,905 --> 00:27:55,770
BAMBINO: Fair.
MAN 2: No way, come on.

371
00:27:55,974 --> 00:27:58,909
Fair. Fair. That's fair.

372
00:27:59,144 --> 00:28:01,009
BAMBINO:
Fair.

373
00:28:04,749 --> 00:28:06,717
[BAND PLAYING JAZZ MUSIC]

374
00:28:07,786 --> 00:28:09,754
[CHATTERING]

375
00:28:59,804 --> 00:29:01,237
LYLE:
Hey.

376
00:29:02,040 --> 00:29:04,600
KATIE: Hi.
- Hey, come on up and sit in.

377
00:29:05,110 --> 00:29:09,069
Oh, no, no, no. I was just curious.
I've never been to a dance like this before.

378
00:29:09,280 --> 00:29:12,272
- No, come on up.
- No. No, no, no. Seriously, no, I can't.

379
00:29:13,818 --> 00:29:16,787
Oh, I'm sorry.
I didn't realize you were afraid.

380
00:29:18,456 --> 00:29:21,550
- Let's go.
- I need you to let her sit in.

381
00:29:22,060 --> 00:29:24,290
- All right, we're about to hit the melody.
- Okay.

382
00:29:24,496 --> 00:29:25,463
You ready?

383
00:29:41,079 --> 00:29:43,775
- Hey, take a verse.
- What?

384
00:29:43,982 --> 00:29:45,677
LYLE:
A verse, a solo. Take a verse.

385
00:29:45,884 --> 00:29:47,215
Uh, there's no solo written here.

386
00:29:47,418 --> 00:29:50,319
LYLE:
Just try it, play what you feel.

387
00:30:17,549 --> 00:30:18,948
[KATIE GIGGLES]

388
00:30:34,966 --> 00:30:36,934
[MEN CONVERSING INDISTINCTLY]

389
00:30:40,305 --> 00:30:41,704
Hey.

390
00:30:42,240 --> 00:30:43,366
[LYLE CLEARS THROAT]

391
00:30:43,575 --> 00:30:46,305
- You weren't so bad in there.
- Oh, yeah, right.

392
00:30:46,511 --> 00:30:48,342
No, I'm serious. Uh...

393
00:30:48,613 --> 00:30:50,046
Started off a little stiff...

394
00:30:50,248 --> 00:30:52,842
- ...but you started to get the hang of it.
- Ha-ha.

395
00:30:53,218 --> 00:30:55,846
When I got up, I thought
I was gonna have a heart attack.

396
00:30:56,054 --> 00:30:58,045
You know,
I was just like that my first time.

397
00:30:58,256 --> 00:31:01,248
- Down at the Avenue.
- What's the Avenue?

398
00:31:04,295 --> 00:31:06,126
You want a drink?

399
00:31:08,800 --> 00:31:10,097
Sure.

400
00:31:14,539 --> 00:31:17,838
LYLE:
Oh, so Central Avenue, downtown L.A.

401
00:31:18,710 --> 00:31:20,405
All the best players in the country
go there.

402
00:31:20,612 --> 00:31:22,170
- Oh.
- And so this one night...

403
00:31:22,380 --> 00:31:26,043
...uh, somehow I got up the nerve
to just go on down there for jam night.

404
00:31:26,251 --> 00:31:28,913
- By myself.
- Oh, my gosh.

405
00:31:29,120 --> 00:31:31,748
I mean, I was so nervous...

406
00:31:31,956 --> 00:31:34,186
...I just stood by the edge of the stage.

407
00:31:34,392 --> 00:31:36,485
Everyone was looking at me
funny because...

408
00:31:36,694 --> 00:31:39,561
I mean, it's a hundred percent
colored people over there.

409
00:31:40,798 --> 00:31:42,231
Oh.

410
00:31:42,634 --> 00:31:47,628
So, um, they finally call my name
and I put my horn to my lips.

411
00:31:49,474 --> 00:31:51,408
- And nothing.
- No.

412
00:31:51,609 --> 00:31:53,907
I could not play a note.

413
00:31:54,112 --> 00:31:56,842
But, you know, there was this piano guy.

414
00:31:57,048 --> 00:32:01,508
He was this old cat.
He looked at me and he said:

415
00:32:01,719 --> 00:32:05,655
- "Go ahead, son. Play a verse."
- Ha-ha-ha-ha. Oh, my God.

416
00:32:05,857 --> 00:32:10,317
But I did. I did. I started playing...

417
00:32:10,528 --> 00:32:12,496
...and it was amazing.

418
00:32:13,464 --> 00:32:16,558
Me, up there...

419
00:32:16,768 --> 00:32:19,430
...with guys from Count Basie's band.

420
00:32:20,071 --> 00:32:21,231
Wow.

421
00:32:21,439 --> 00:32:24,931
Okay, I never even knew
that Japs played jazz.

422
00:32:26,511 --> 00:32:28,604
I'm not a Jap.

423
00:32:29,547 --> 00:32:32,345
I was born here just like you.

424
00:32:32,550 --> 00:32:34,916
I'm sorry, I didn't me--

425
00:32:37,956 --> 00:32:40,424
Thanks for letting me play with the band.

426
00:32:46,297 --> 00:32:48,822
LYLE: Hey, big brother.
Worn out from all that dancing?

427
00:32:49,033 --> 00:32:51,866
Yeah. It's hot in there.

428
00:32:52,070 --> 00:32:53,731
Give me a cigarette.

429
00:32:54,138 --> 00:32:58,404
- Didn't know you still had those moves.
- Yeah, that Nancy girl's running off my feet.

430
00:33:02,814 --> 00:33:04,213
What are you doing out here?

431
00:33:04,415 --> 00:33:07,782
- Oh, you know, just needed some air.
- Yeah.

432
00:33:07,986 --> 00:33:09,419
So?

433
00:33:09,654 --> 00:33:10,916
LANE:
Hmm?

434
00:33:12,991 --> 00:33:15,789
Why'd you ask her to come up
and play like that?

435
00:33:17,128 --> 00:33:18,356
[LYLE SCOFFS]

436
00:33:18,563 --> 00:33:20,190
Thanks, Dad.

437
00:33:32,877 --> 00:33:36,711
Our people fighting and dying
and these people here...

438
00:33:37,448 --> 00:33:38,881
[BILLY GROANS]

439
00:33:39,884 --> 00:33:42,079
They start a baseball league.

440
00:33:42,286 --> 00:33:44,186
BILLY:
They have dances, beauty pageants.

441
00:33:44,389 --> 00:33:48,689
Ah, Watson and his Quakers
made this place into a summer camp.

442
00:33:50,228 --> 00:33:53,129
I've become a goddamn babysitter.

443
00:33:59,437 --> 00:34:02,304
MACK:
Will you get that ball for us?

444
00:34:03,041 --> 00:34:05,134
BILLY:
The ball there.

445
00:34:05,343 --> 00:34:06,810
Oh, sorry.

446
00:34:07,011 --> 00:34:08,410
No English.

447
00:34:09,080 --> 00:34:11,947
Get the ball, pick it up,
throw it back here.

448
00:34:12,150 --> 00:34:14,084
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

449
00:34:17,488 --> 00:34:19,479
You, you understand English.

450
00:34:19,690 --> 00:34:21,783
BILLY:
Throw it back here.

451
00:34:21,993 --> 00:34:23,620
If you can't get it all the way...

452
00:34:23,828 --> 00:34:26,558
...just try to get it as close to Mack,
right there.

453
00:34:44,782 --> 00:34:46,841
You got a pretty good arm.

454
00:34:47,452 --> 00:34:51,013
How about betting a buck and see
if you can strike out the sergeant there?

455
00:34:51,222 --> 00:34:52,689
Five bucks.

456
00:34:54,025 --> 00:34:55,287
Five?

457
00:34:55,493 --> 00:34:57,222
I'll put up the 5.

458
00:35:04,402 --> 00:35:06,666
BILLY:
One at bat. Maximum seven pitches.

459
00:35:06,871 --> 00:35:10,204
Hit, walk or strike out.
You strike me out, you win 5 bucks.

460
00:35:10,408 --> 00:35:13,434
You don't, I win.

461
00:35:19,684 --> 00:35:24,053
Call the shot, Billy. Like Babe Ruth.
Show him where you're gonna hit it.

462
00:35:29,093 --> 00:35:30,321
[BILLY GRUNTS]

463
00:35:30,528 --> 00:35:31,620
Attaboy, Lyle.

464
00:35:31,829 --> 00:35:36,027
You guys didn't know he had a scholarship
to play baseball, did you, huh?

465
00:35:36,234 --> 00:35:37,201
[NORI LAUGHING]

466
00:35:37,401 --> 00:35:40,063
You picked up English quick,
didn't you, Tojo?

467
00:35:40,271 --> 00:35:41,533
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

468
00:35:41,739 --> 00:35:44,139
Just a little bit.

469
00:35:55,786 --> 00:35:57,151
[BILLY GRUNTS]

470
00:35:57,355 --> 00:35:59,016
How about that? Huh?

471
00:36:00,625 --> 00:36:03,059
Zero and two.
You wanna double that bet?

472
00:36:03,594 --> 00:36:04,822
LYLE:
Make it 10?

473
00:36:05,029 --> 00:36:06,394
[NORI MUTTERS]

474
00:36:06,597 --> 00:36:08,360
Ten bucks.

475
00:36:09,534 --> 00:36:11,559
NORI:
Throw them in there, Lyle.

476
00:36:11,769 --> 00:36:13,202
Easy money, Lyle.

477
00:36:13,404 --> 00:36:16,567
We got a couple of suckers
on our hands here.

478
00:36:21,746 --> 00:36:23,907
- Ball one.
- That was right down the middle.

479
00:36:24,115 --> 00:36:26,583
Off the outside corner. One and two.

480
00:36:36,260 --> 00:36:38,888
- Ball two.
- That was strike three and you know it.

481
00:36:39,096 --> 00:36:41,690
Just a little bit high,
don't you think there, Macky?

482
00:36:41,899 --> 00:36:46,131
That's right.
Just a little bit, just a little bit high.

483
00:36:46,337 --> 00:36:49,101
- Bullshit.
- Hey, watch your mouth, boy.

484
00:37:02,286 --> 00:37:05,653
Ha. Not much question about that one.

485
00:37:05,856 --> 00:37:07,118
BILLY:
Full count. Three and two.

486
00:37:07,325 --> 00:37:10,055
Let's see what you do
with money on the line.

487
00:37:13,931 --> 00:37:15,626
Ball four.

488
00:37:16,167 --> 00:37:17,657
Where's my money, hotshot?

489
00:37:18,603 --> 00:37:20,764
You couldn't hit me
if your life depended on it.

490
00:37:20,972 --> 00:37:22,940
You weren't even close those first two.

491
00:37:23,574 --> 00:37:25,201
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

492
00:37:27,878 --> 00:37:29,402
NORI:
Ten bucks.

493
00:37:30,181 --> 00:37:31,705
I handle the money.

494
00:37:31,916 --> 00:37:34,851
Here's your 10 bucks.
And thank you.

495
00:37:35,052 --> 00:37:38,783
Thank you for a great demonstration
of skill and sportsmanship.

496
00:37:39,257 --> 00:37:41,225
Like we say in the old country:

497
00:37:41,425 --> 00:37:43,086
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

498
00:37:56,741 --> 00:37:58,470
Let it go, Lyle.

499
00:37:59,310 --> 00:38:01,175
Let it go.

500
00:38:03,848 --> 00:38:08,979
Who the hell does he think he is,
thinking he could play baseball?

501
00:38:10,988 --> 00:38:13,354
This had nothing to do with baseball.

502
00:38:13,758 --> 00:38:17,717
[LYLE PLAYING SAXOPHONE
AND KATIE PLAYING PIANO]

503
00:38:39,850 --> 00:38:41,181
[KATIE SIGHS]

504
00:38:41,385 --> 00:38:43,751
I start getting it
and then my fingers won't do it.

505
00:38:43,954 --> 00:38:47,117
It's okay. Just take it again at half tempo,
but this time listen.

506
00:38:47,325 --> 00:38:51,921
No, no. Don't go easy on me.
I wanna play it fast, jazz-style.

507
00:39:05,209 --> 00:39:08,667
See? It's not about playing it fast.

508
00:39:09,146 --> 00:39:13,207
Sometimes it's more about what you're
not playing than what you are playing.

509
00:39:14,018 --> 00:39:16,953
- You just have to listen.
- I am listening.

510
00:39:17,154 --> 00:39:20,351
No, you're not listening.
You don't even know how to listen.

511
00:39:20,558 --> 00:39:21,889
I listen.

512
00:39:22,093 --> 00:39:23,253
Hey, I know these guys.

513
00:39:23,461 --> 00:39:25,952
Old guys. They told me
they spent their whole lives...

514
00:39:26,163 --> 00:39:28,154
...trying to learn
how to play one phrase.

515
00:39:28,566 --> 00:39:30,693
Listening to it,
getting it right.

516
00:39:30,901 --> 00:39:33,995
You know, the sound. Getting a feel for it.

517
00:39:34,538 --> 00:39:35,971
Trust me, okay?

518
00:39:36,474 --> 00:39:40,001
- Let's try it again, slowly.
- Okay.

519
00:40:55,219 --> 00:40:57,346
[BAT CRACKS
AND THEN CROWD CHEERING]

520
00:40:57,555 --> 00:41:01,252
ANNOUNCER: Tully rounding first
and headed for second.

521
00:41:01,492 --> 00:41:02,857
[GRUNTING]

522
00:41:03,060 --> 00:41:04,960
Look out.

523
00:41:07,865 --> 00:41:09,560
Feel like you can use a haircut?

524
00:41:09,767 --> 00:41:11,735
Don't forget about Ed's Barbershop.

525
00:41:11,936 --> 00:41:14,996
ANNOUNCER:
Cut it right, cut it at Ed's.

526
00:41:18,108 --> 00:41:21,805
- Feels good to be in first place, don't it?
- Yeah, not bad, huh?

527
00:41:23,047 --> 00:41:24,742
Good ball game.

528
00:41:32,890 --> 00:41:34,357
Billy.

529
00:41:35,359 --> 00:41:38,419
I thought you'd wanna see him
as soon as possible.

530
00:41:45,769 --> 00:41:47,737
Oh, Jesus.

531
00:41:49,907 --> 00:41:51,238
Billy's son.

532
00:42:25,009 --> 00:42:26,567
- No.
WOMAN: Sit down.

533
00:42:26,777 --> 00:42:28,335
- No.
WOMAN: Sit down.

534
00:42:28,579 --> 00:42:30,547
[SHIRLEY SOBBING]

535
00:42:56,473 --> 00:42:58,441
[SINGING "SILENT NIGHT"]

536
00:43:02,713 --> 00:43:04,681
[CHATTERING]

537
00:43:10,421 --> 00:43:13,288
[CONVERSING IN JAPANESE
AND THEN LAUGHING]

538
00:43:29,473 --> 00:43:31,532
Mom, Dad, Lyle.

539
00:43:32,910 --> 00:43:35,242
I have something important I wanna say.

540
00:43:37,615 --> 00:43:39,173
I enlisted.

541
00:43:39,984 --> 00:43:42,043
LANE:
I joined the Army.

542
00:43:42,252 --> 00:43:45,119
I can't be in here anymore.

543
00:43:45,322 --> 00:43:49,315
- You should have come to me--
- I feel like I'm not doing anything.

544
00:43:50,194 --> 00:43:53,686
- I accepted what happened to us--
- You accepted it?

545
00:43:53,897 --> 00:43:55,956
I accepted it
because we didn't have a choice.

546
00:43:56,166 --> 00:43:58,134
But now we have a choice.

547
00:43:58,335 --> 00:44:02,465
Now I can prove that I'm as American
as anybody else.

548
00:44:02,673 --> 00:44:05,574
You just get smarter by the minute,
don't you, Lane?

549
00:44:07,911 --> 00:44:10,709
Do you understand how much shame
you've brought our family?

550
00:44:10,914 --> 00:44:13,906
- Lane, that's enough.
- I need to do this. I need to tell him this.

551
00:44:14,118 --> 00:44:17,087
I'm the only one in here
who's not afraid to say what I think.

552
00:44:17,688 --> 00:44:19,178
Lyle.

553
00:44:19,957 --> 00:44:22,653
You lost a scholarship. Big deal.

554
00:44:23,827 --> 00:44:26,853
Everyone in here
has lost something, Lyle.

555
00:44:28,198 --> 00:44:30,166
LANE:
And no one complains.

556
00:44:31,168 --> 00:44:34,763
No one says anything,
no one cries, except you.

557
00:44:35,739 --> 00:44:37,036
Only you.

558
00:44:39,243 --> 00:44:40,904
You know what?

559
00:44:42,913 --> 00:44:44,437
You go.

560
00:44:45,449 --> 00:44:47,280
Go fight.

561
00:44:49,820 --> 00:44:51,845
You go over there...

562
00:44:52,723 --> 00:44:54,714
...you get yourself killed.

563
00:44:54,925 --> 00:44:56,756
See what that proves.

564
00:45:29,526 --> 00:45:31,255
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

565
00:45:32,763 --> 00:45:34,492
One thousand stitches.

566
00:45:36,467 --> 00:45:42,372
EMI: One thousand mothers here
have each sewn one red stitch.

567
00:45:43,207 --> 00:45:45,607
This, for my son.

568
00:45:46,577 --> 00:45:48,545
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

569
00:45:56,453 --> 00:45:57,852
Lane.

570
00:45:59,423 --> 00:46:02,586
EMI: As long as you wear this <i>senninbari</i>
around your waist...

571
00:46:03,560 --> 00:46:06,324
...you'll be protected from harm.

572
00:46:14,338 --> 00:46:16,067
Thanks, Mom.

573
00:46:21,645 --> 00:46:23,909
Thinking what I'm thinking?

574
00:46:24,882 --> 00:46:27,407
I doubt that very much, Mack.

575
00:46:28,118 --> 00:46:30,814
I know they're gonna be killing Krauts
and not their own...

576
00:46:31,021 --> 00:46:33,615
...but don't make no sense
letting them join our Army.

577
00:46:33,824 --> 00:46:36,315
LANE:
I will wear this with pride.

578
00:46:36,794 --> 00:46:38,853
And the thought of you...

579
00:46:39,396 --> 00:46:42,729
...all of you,
will remind me of why I'm there.

580
00:46:43,901 --> 00:46:46,369
LANE:
Of what I'm fighting for.

581
00:46:50,140 --> 00:46:52,802
And thanks for coming to see me off.

582
00:46:54,478 --> 00:46:56,343
LANE:
I appreciate it.

583
00:46:59,783 --> 00:47:01,182
So I guess this is it.

584
00:47:03,353 --> 00:47:05,116
Bye, Mom.

585
00:47:11,395 --> 00:47:12,862
[EMI SIGHS]

586
00:47:13,363 --> 00:47:15,331
LANE: I'll be fine.
- Yes.

587
00:47:15,532 --> 00:47:17,124
Yes.

588
00:47:24,875 --> 00:47:26,536
Dad.

589
00:47:29,513 --> 00:47:30,878
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

590
00:47:37,988 --> 00:47:39,956
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

591
00:47:44,328 --> 00:47:47,229
I am what I am because of you.

592
00:47:52,102 --> 00:47:53,535
[TRUCK ENGINE STARTS]

593
00:47:56,440 --> 00:47:57,964
GIRL 1:
Bye, Lane.

594
00:47:58,675 --> 00:47:59,903
GIRL 1: Bye.
GIRL 2: Bye.

595
00:48:00,110 --> 00:48:01,907
MAN:
Come back soon.

596
00:48:05,582 --> 00:48:08,551
[GIRLS SINGING
"AMERICA THE BEAUTIFUL"]

597
00:48:15,459 --> 00:48:18,428
[MAN THUMPS TRUCK
AND SHOUTS INDISTINCTLY]

598
00:48:35,012 --> 00:48:38,971
[LYLE PLAYING "AMERICA THE BEAUTIFUL"
ON SAXOPHONE]

599
00:49:03,240 --> 00:49:04,707
EMI:
Kazuo?

600
00:49:07,878 --> 00:49:09,846
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

601
00:49:18,221 --> 00:49:20,155
[EMI HUMMING]

602
00:49:50,153 --> 00:49:52,121
[KAZ SINGING IN JAPANESE]

603
00:51:11,835 --> 00:51:13,166
REPORTER:
<i>Camp Shelby, Mississippi.</i>

604
00:51:13,370 --> 00:51:18,433
<i>The Japanese-American 442nd</i>
<i>Regimental Combat Team in training...</i>

605
00:51:18,642 --> 00:51:20,872
<i>...preparing to fight for their country...</i>

606
00:51:21,078 --> 00:51:23,945
<i>...and the American ideals</i>
<i>that are a part of their upbringing.</i>

607
00:51:24,147 --> 00:51:26,274
<i>Democracy and equality of opportunity...</i>

608
00:51:26,483 --> 00:51:29,452
<i>...regardless of race, creed,</i>
<i>color or ancestry.</i>

609
00:51:29,653 --> 00:51:34,113
<i>Their spirit is typified</i>
<i>by their slogan of "Go for Broke."</i>

610
00:51:34,324 --> 00:51:40,263
<i>Meaning "shoot the works, risk everything,</i>
<i>go all out, never let up."</i>

611
00:51:40,464 --> 00:51:43,558
<i>Go for broke indeed.</i>

612
00:51:44,401 --> 00:51:45,868
- Go for broke.
- Go for broke.

613
00:51:46,069 --> 00:51:48,367
- Go for broke.
- Go for broke.

614
00:51:49,139 --> 00:51:50,800
MAN 1:
Go for broke.

615
00:51:51,007 --> 00:51:53,202
MAN 2: Go for broke.
WOMAN: Go for broke.

616
00:51:53,410 --> 00:51:54,638
Go for broke.

617
00:52:09,359 --> 00:52:13,318
[JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING
ON SAXOPHONE AND PIANO]

618
00:52:37,721 --> 00:52:38,949
[DOOR OPENS]

619
00:52:39,156 --> 00:52:40,714
BILLY:
Katie.

620
00:52:40,924 --> 00:52:43,415
BILLY: Katie, you in here?
KATIE: Yeah, I'm just here.

621
00:52:43,627 --> 00:52:46,994
I, uh, got off a little early, so if you're
done now, I can drive us.

622
00:52:47,197 --> 00:52:51,293
Oh. Okay. I just have to finish cleaning up
a couple things back here.

623
00:52:52,269 --> 00:52:54,396
Where are your Jap girls?

624
00:52:54,604 --> 00:52:56,697
They left a little while ago.

625
00:52:56,907 --> 00:52:59,899
I'll just-- I'll meet you at the truck.
I'll be there in a minute.

626
00:53:00,877 --> 00:53:02,344
All right.

627
00:53:10,520 --> 00:53:12,488
[KATIE & LYLE LAUGHING]

628
00:53:15,125 --> 00:53:19,061
EMI:
Oh, Lyle. Lyle, come here. Come.

629
00:53:20,530 --> 00:53:23,328
Did you see this in the camp paper?

630
00:53:23,900 --> 00:53:26,391
The Quakers are gonna
offer a scholarship.

631
00:53:26,603 --> 00:53:28,662
"One player from the camp league...

632
00:53:28,872 --> 00:53:31,534
...all expenses paid,
to the University of Delaware."

633
00:53:32,309 --> 00:53:34,675
LYLE: Whoever wins this
can get out of here, go to college?

634
00:53:34,878 --> 00:53:36,072
EMI:
Yes.

635
00:53:37,781 --> 00:53:39,715
[WHISPERING]
He's here. Tell him.

636
00:53:41,218 --> 00:53:43,379
Have you seen the paper this morning?

637
00:53:43,587 --> 00:53:45,578
If the Quakers will offer
this scholarship...

638
00:53:45,789 --> 00:53:48,451
...then I can win this
and I can get out of here.

639
00:53:50,193 --> 00:53:53,629
Did you hear what I said? I can get this.
You know that.

640
00:53:53,830 --> 00:53:55,354
Now...

641
00:53:56,299 --> 00:53:59,462
...I asked you before, you said no to me.

642
00:54:00,437 --> 00:54:03,668
- Kazuo, what he's trying to say is--
- Emi.

643
00:54:16,086 --> 00:54:17,610
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

644
00:54:22,425 --> 00:54:24,325
I just want a chance for this.

645
00:54:25,362 --> 00:54:28,661
LYLE: I know that I haven't been--
- No booze.

646
00:54:30,767 --> 00:54:32,132
Yeah, yeah, okay.

647
00:54:32,335 --> 00:54:34,394
KAZ:
No gambling.

648
00:54:35,071 --> 00:54:36,732
All right.

649
00:54:37,007 --> 00:54:39,100
No seeing that girl.

650
00:54:39,542 --> 00:54:40,941
What?

651
00:54:41,978 --> 00:54:43,775
What does she have to do
with anything?

652
00:54:45,215 --> 00:54:47,342
Everyone in camp knows.

653
00:54:47,550 --> 00:54:49,040
Everyone is talking.

654
00:54:49,519 --> 00:54:50,952
I don't care what they say.

655
00:54:53,923 --> 00:54:55,550
I say.

656
00:54:56,226 --> 00:54:57,853
No <i>hakujin</i>.

657
00:55:07,837 --> 00:55:10,670
Kaz, it could be a chance for him.

658
00:55:10,874 --> 00:55:12,364
Quiet.

659
00:55:13,276 --> 00:55:15,301
Lyle. Lyle.

660
00:55:15,512 --> 00:55:18,208
EMI: If your father won't let you play
on his team...

661
00:55:18,415 --> 00:55:20,212
...there are other teams to play for.

662
00:55:20,417 --> 00:55:23,545
- You can--
- You tell my son to turn his back on me?

663
00:55:27,924 --> 00:55:29,892
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

664
00:55:34,097 --> 00:55:36,065
[EMI SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

665
00:55:38,702 --> 00:55:41,830
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

666
00:55:42,672 --> 00:55:44,139
No.

667
00:55:48,044 --> 00:55:50,012
[CROWD CHEERING]

668
00:55:52,649 --> 00:55:53,911
Next batter.

669
00:55:54,117 --> 00:55:56,085
[BAMBINO PLAYING UKULELE]

670
00:56:01,991 --> 00:56:03,185
All right.

671
00:56:03,493 --> 00:56:06,257
Whoo! What you get? What you get?
Give me one, bro.

672
00:56:10,133 --> 00:56:11,327
- Strike one.
- Aw.

673
00:56:11,534 --> 00:56:13,468
Come on, brother.
You need some glasses.

674
00:56:13,670 --> 00:56:14,864
BAMBINO:
Strike.

675
00:56:15,071 --> 00:56:17,733
BAMBINO: Give me another one.
- Eh, never could stand Hawaiian music.

676
00:56:17,941 --> 00:56:19,374
Well, you know <i>da kine</i> jazz?

677
00:56:19,576 --> 00:56:21,373
Give me one big headache, bro.

678
00:56:25,248 --> 00:56:27,011
[CROWD GROANS]

679
00:56:28,918 --> 00:56:31,284
MAN: Foul ball.
BAMBINO: Jeez.

680
00:56:31,488 --> 00:56:34,980
- It was a long strike.
- You know aloha means "hello," yeah?

681
00:56:35,191 --> 00:56:36,681
Ha-ha. Whoo.

682
00:56:36,893 --> 00:56:38,326
BAMBINO:
What you get? What you get?

683
00:56:38,528 --> 00:56:39,961
Whoa. Whoo!

684
00:56:40,163 --> 00:56:43,132
Okay. All right. All right.

685
00:56:44,234 --> 00:56:46,759
You know, it also means
"I love you," brother.

686
00:56:47,170 --> 00:56:49,365
What you get? What you get?

687
00:56:50,006 --> 00:56:51,098
[BAMBINO GRUNTS]

688
00:56:51,307 --> 00:56:53,241
Hey, doesn't it also mean goodbye?

689
00:56:53,910 --> 00:56:55,104
[BAMBINO CHUCKLES]

690
00:56:55,311 --> 00:56:57,142
Aloha.

691
00:56:59,649 --> 00:57:01,742
I had an idea
about when I win the scholarship.

692
00:57:01,951 --> 00:57:03,885
How do you know you're gonna win it?

693
00:57:04,087 --> 00:57:05,554
- I'll win it.
- Ha-ha-ha.

694
00:57:05,889 --> 00:57:09,882
But when I get out of here, I was thinking
that you would come with me.

695
00:57:10,093 --> 00:57:13,256
- Come with you?
- Yeah.

696
00:57:13,563 --> 00:57:17,021
I've been thinking about it a lot.
I mean, you're a good musician, Katie.

697
00:57:17,233 --> 00:57:19,929
A really good musician,
but you need to learn more.

698
00:57:20,136 --> 00:57:21,831
You need to play with other people...

699
00:57:22,038 --> 00:57:25,838
...you need to, you know,
get more experience.

700
00:57:26,709 --> 00:57:28,267
Then maybe one day, you know...

701
00:57:28,478 --> 00:57:32,539
...you could play professionally
or you could teach.

702
00:57:32,749 --> 00:57:36,412
Uh, Lyle, I'm--
That school is in Delaware.

703
00:57:36,619 --> 00:57:38,780
I've never been outside of Abraham
in my life.

704
00:57:38,988 --> 00:57:40,546
Yeah, but that is the point, Katie.

705
00:57:40,757 --> 00:57:43,555
You've got to get out of Abraham.

706
00:57:43,760 --> 00:57:45,489
There's nothing there.

707
00:57:45,695 --> 00:57:49,290
Delaware has this
really good music department.

708
00:57:50,166 --> 00:57:52,726
And I already got you an application.

709
00:57:53,636 --> 00:57:55,069
We--

710
00:58:00,210 --> 00:58:02,610
I want you to come with me.

711
00:58:06,916 --> 00:58:08,508
Yes.

712
00:58:09,385 --> 00:58:10,750
I will.

713
00:58:10,954 --> 00:58:12,615
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

714
00:58:13,223 --> 00:58:15,453
BILLY: Ed, guess what.
Yankees are looking for a catcher.

715
00:58:15,658 --> 00:58:17,819
Dapper Don might be coming down here.

716
00:58:18,027 --> 00:58:20,393
I don't give a shit about that.

717
00:58:21,164 --> 00:58:22,529
What's the matter with you?

718
00:58:23,366 --> 00:58:27,234
I always figured Katie and my boy Jackie
would be together someday.

719
00:58:28,071 --> 00:58:30,938
And I even came to think of her
as my own daughter.

720
00:58:32,041 --> 00:58:33,770
Yeah, and?

721
00:58:35,979 --> 00:58:37,742
Now I don't.

722
00:58:42,118 --> 00:58:43,915
You've been seeing some Jap?

723
00:58:45,722 --> 00:58:47,246
What?

724
00:58:48,591 --> 00:58:51,025
You've been seeing some Jap boy?

725
00:58:51,227 --> 00:58:54,560
- Billy, what--?
- Answer the question, Katie.

726
00:58:55,899 --> 00:58:58,163
- No.
- No?

727
00:58:59,102 --> 00:59:01,127
You haven't been
seeing that Jap, Nomura?

728
00:59:02,338 --> 00:59:05,364
No. No, ha-ha, of course not.

729
00:59:08,177 --> 00:59:10,042
Well, what Ed heard is wrong.

730
00:59:10,947 --> 00:59:12,812
BILLY:
I know you wouldn't do that.

731
00:59:14,384 --> 00:59:16,443
I know you would never do
anything like that.

732
00:59:16,653 --> 00:59:18,314
BILLY:
Not to me, not to our family.

733
00:59:20,623 --> 00:59:22,818
Not to the memory of your brother.

734
00:59:41,711 --> 00:59:43,679
I spoke to Director Watson...

735
00:59:43,880 --> 00:59:47,816
...about how to ease tension
between us and the people in town.

736
00:59:48,017 --> 00:59:50,315
We had an idea to have a game...

737
00:59:50,520 --> 00:59:53,921
...between your baseball team
and our Topaz team.

738
00:59:54,123 --> 00:59:55,317
Maybe we have--

739
00:59:55,525 --> 00:59:59,461
No. Nobody on our team
would ever set foot in that camp.

740
00:59:59,662 --> 01:00:01,061
JOE:
Uh, delivery's running late, uh...

741
01:00:01,264 --> 01:00:04,233
They just called,
said they'll be about 15, 20 minutes.

742
01:00:04,434 --> 01:00:06,561
I got a package to pick up
at the post office.

743
01:00:06,769 --> 01:00:09,533
Take care of their order
when the delivery comes.

744
01:00:12,175 --> 01:00:14,769
A basket for you and your wife.

745
01:00:15,945 --> 01:00:17,378
JOE:
Thank you, Kaz.

746
01:00:33,863 --> 01:00:35,888
This town is sick to death of you people.

747
01:00:36,366 --> 01:00:38,266
Why don't you go back
where you came from?

748
01:00:38,468 --> 01:00:40,129
I'm from Los Angeles.

749
01:00:50,513 --> 01:00:51,844
[GRUNTING]

750
01:00:58,621 --> 01:01:01,181
LYLE:
No. Get off.

751
01:01:04,327 --> 01:01:06,659
You hungry? Go ahead, eat.

752
01:01:07,130 --> 01:01:08,529
Eat!

753
01:01:09,232 --> 01:01:11,291
Hey! Hey, knock it off!

754
01:01:11,501 --> 01:01:13,799
The hell are you doing out here, Nomura?

755
01:01:14,003 --> 01:01:15,834
Nomura? This that kid?

756
01:01:16,372 --> 01:01:17,862
[LYLE SCREAMS]

757
01:01:20,677 --> 01:01:21,939
BILLY:
All right, that's enough.

758
01:01:22,145 --> 01:01:25,979
Break it up. Break it up.
Come here. Break it up!

759
01:01:26,182 --> 01:01:28,514
Everybody, go on. Get out of here.
Get out of here.

760
01:01:29,952 --> 01:01:31,943
BILLY:
Take it home, Ed.

761
01:01:33,389 --> 01:01:36,256
All right. Okay.

762
01:01:39,328 --> 01:01:41,193
- Are you okay?
LYLE: Yeah.

763
01:01:41,397 --> 01:01:44,025
- Okay?
BILLY: Get him in the jeep.

764
01:01:45,535 --> 01:01:47,526
LYLE: No, I'm fine.
- Okay.

765
01:01:54,310 --> 01:01:57,871
SHIRLEY: Who told you that one? Oh.
- Mary Beth.

766
01:01:59,382 --> 01:02:00,849
[SHIRLEY CHUCKLES]

767
01:02:01,584 --> 01:02:06,078
We had a little trouble in town today.
One of the prisoners tried to run off.

768
01:02:06,289 --> 01:02:08,120
Run off?
Where are they gonna run to?

769
01:02:08,324 --> 01:02:11,555
- There's nothing around for 300 miles.
- He wasn't trying to escape.

770
01:02:11,761 --> 01:02:14,389
He came into town with us
to get some supplies...

771
01:02:14,597 --> 01:02:17,157
...and then he decided
he'd just wander off...

772
01:02:17,366 --> 01:02:19,300
...and get himself a burger.

773
01:02:20,837 --> 01:02:22,828
That Nomura kid.

774
01:02:27,443 --> 01:02:28,774
What did you do to him?

775
01:02:28,978 --> 01:02:30,445
BILLY:
Me? Nothing.

776
01:02:30,646 --> 01:02:33,114
Couple fellas in town
roughed him up a little bit.

777
01:02:42,358 --> 01:02:45,589
- Excuse me for just a second.
- Sit your ass down.

778
01:02:52,168 --> 01:02:54,295
You're not going back
to that camp, Katie.

779
01:02:54,937 --> 01:02:57,929
BILLY: Not tomorrow, not the next day.
Not ever.

780
01:02:58,141 --> 01:03:01,042
- What?
- You've been fired from your job.

781
01:03:01,544 --> 01:03:04,672
BILLY: You try to go back into that camp,
the guards will stop you.

782
01:03:13,256 --> 01:03:14,621
[DOOR SLAMS]

783
01:03:17,527 --> 01:03:18,789
[BILLY SIGHS]

784
01:03:37,213 --> 01:03:40,182
Heard you didn't get the scholarship
because of your injury.

785
01:03:41,184 --> 01:03:42,913
NORI:
That's too bad.

786
01:03:51,828 --> 01:03:56,492
Things happen. Whatever happens,
we have to deal with it.

787
01:03:59,735 --> 01:04:02,499
Tough luck, kid.

788
01:04:02,705 --> 01:04:04,832
Deal with it.

789
01:04:15,384 --> 01:04:19,650
REPORTER: <i>The Japanese-American</i>
<i>442nd Regimental Combat Team...</i>

790
01:04:19,856 --> 01:04:24,384
<i>...moving up from their battles in Italy</i>
<i>into the Vosges mountains in France...</i>

791
01:04:24,861 --> 01:04:27,955
<i>...fighting in tough terrain</i>
<i>against seasoned German forces...</i>

792
01:04:28,164 --> 01:04:32,624
<i>...trying to rescue a lost battalion</i>
<i>of fellow Americans.</i>

793
01:04:33,269 --> 01:04:37,137
<i>Mission after mission, these stalwart</i>
<i>fighting men are proving themselves...</i>

794
01:04:37,340 --> 01:04:39,774
<i>...bringing honor to themselves</i>
<i>and the nation...</i>

795
01:04:39,976 --> 01:04:42,877
<i>...that is proud to call them citizens.</i>

796
01:04:50,853 --> 01:04:52,582
Hey, Billy.

797
01:04:52,788 --> 01:04:55,552
You know anybody in the Texas 36th?

798
01:04:55,758 --> 01:04:58,386
No, I think Mack knows
a bunch of guys with them.

799
01:04:58,594 --> 01:05:02,462
Well, the Krauts cut them off
up in the Vosges mountains in France.

800
01:05:02,665 --> 01:05:04,599
They got ripped up bad.

801
01:05:05,201 --> 01:05:07,999
None of our other guys
could get up the mountain to help them.

802
01:05:09,038 --> 01:05:10,801
Except for them.

803
01:05:11,140 --> 01:05:13,734
The 442nd, they took 800 casualties...

804
01:05:13,943 --> 01:05:17,003
...to save 211 guys in the 36th.

805
01:05:18,881 --> 01:05:20,678
These guys...

806
01:05:21,751 --> 01:05:23,844
...they're all from Topaz.

807
01:05:48,444 --> 01:05:52,744
Barber says to her, "Sweetheart,
you're gonna get hair on your Twinkie."

808
01:05:52,949 --> 01:05:55,884
She says, "I know.
I'm gonna get boobies too."

809
01:05:56,118 --> 01:05:57,551
[ED LAUGHS]

810
01:06:05,294 --> 01:06:07,057
Just got off the bus from Phoenix.

811
01:06:07,263 --> 01:06:08,696
On my way to Topaz.

812
01:06:08,898 --> 01:06:09,830
[LANE SIGHS]

813
01:06:10,066 --> 01:06:13,092
Thought I'd get cleaned up
before seeing my folks.

814
01:06:13,502 --> 01:06:15,800
The back's kind of raggedy...

815
01:06:16,005 --> 01:06:18,269
...so think it could use a trim right now.

816
01:06:18,741 --> 01:06:21,505
Billy gets called up, we're gonna be
missing a pretty big bat next year.

817
01:06:21,711 --> 01:06:23,008
Hmm. Not gonna be as easy...

818
01:06:23,212 --> 01:06:26,272
- ...to win a championship again.
JOE: Mm-hm.

819
01:06:28,150 --> 01:06:31,586
Still, as long as Grover's with us,
you know, we got a good arm there.

820
01:06:31,821 --> 01:06:33,846
I'm kind of in a hurry here.

821
01:06:34,323 --> 01:06:37,087
An MP's picking me up
in a couple minutes.

822
01:06:41,130 --> 01:06:42,927
I don't cut Jap hair.

823
01:06:48,604 --> 01:06:50,504
NORRIS:
Lieutenant Nomura.

824
01:06:57,213 --> 01:07:00,114
Corporal Norris, here to pick you up.

825
01:07:00,316 --> 01:07:01,715
At ease.

826
01:07:03,352 --> 01:07:04,979
Welcome back, sir.

827
01:07:05,721 --> 01:07:07,484
Thank you.

828
01:07:49,965 --> 01:07:51,557
Hi, Mom.

829
01:08:02,578 --> 01:08:04,512
[EMI SOBBING]

830
01:08:11,187 --> 01:08:12,620
Dad.

831
01:08:22,565 --> 01:08:23,964
[SPEAKING IN JAPANESE]

832
01:08:50,059 --> 01:08:53,756
KAZ:
Lane, we kept everything.

833
01:08:54,330 --> 01:08:56,127
He wanted to show you
how he kept them.

834
01:08:56,332 --> 01:08:59,665
And I was telling him
that he was acting like a librarian.

835
01:08:59,869 --> 01:09:00,927
And the news.

836
01:09:01,170 --> 01:09:02,102
[LANE CHUCKLES]

837
01:09:02,338 --> 01:09:05,273
And I really think
that he can still get a new job as a librarian.

838
01:09:05,508 --> 01:09:06,907
[DOOR OPENS]

839
01:09:08,511 --> 01:09:11,173
Hey. I heard you were back.

840
01:09:11,614 --> 01:09:12,774
Hi, Lyle.

841
01:09:13,015 --> 01:09:15,483
Ahem.
Uh, how've you been?

842
01:09:16,652 --> 01:09:17,584
Fine.

843
01:09:17,820 --> 01:09:20,983
I went around to neighbors
and got everything you like.

844
01:09:22,091 --> 01:09:24,457
EMI: When Mrs. Watanabe came
with the <i>mochi</i>...

845
01:09:24,660 --> 01:09:28,096
...I thought it was perfect.
I have everything I wanted.

846
01:09:28,330 --> 01:09:30,264
I thought you would've lost more weight.

847
01:09:30,499 --> 01:09:33,195
You'd be like skinny, skinny, skinny.

848
01:09:33,669 --> 01:09:37,070
Now you're gonna have
home cooking again.

849
01:09:37,973 --> 01:09:39,440
Sounds good.

850
01:09:47,383 --> 01:09:49,647
KATIE:
I can't stand it anymore.

851
01:09:50,186 --> 01:09:53,383
I'm doing nothing.
I can't play music, I can't come here.

852
01:09:53,589 --> 01:09:57,389
I'm just stuck in that house
here in Abraham.

853
01:09:58,360 --> 01:09:59,793
I have to do something.

854
01:10:02,665 --> 01:10:04,030
[KATIE SIGHS]

855
01:10:07,636 --> 01:10:09,627
I'm going away.

856
01:10:10,105 --> 01:10:11,436
What?

857
01:10:11,640 --> 01:10:13,733
I am going away...

858
01:10:14,009 --> 01:10:15,909
...on my own.

859
01:10:17,813 --> 01:10:19,542
Where are you going?

860
01:10:19,949 --> 01:10:23,942
I'm going to Delaware. To school.
I got accepted.

861
01:10:24,720 --> 01:10:27,587
No, that wasn't the plan.
You were going there because I was.

862
01:10:27,790 --> 01:10:30,418
I applied because of you, but now it--

863
01:10:30,926 --> 01:10:32,860
I mean,
this is an amazing chance for me.

864
01:10:33,062 --> 01:10:36,862
You're the one who told me I could do this,
I could get out of Abraham. It was you.

865
01:10:37,066 --> 01:10:39,330
You were going there with me.

866
01:10:40,135 --> 01:10:42,160
I can't see you here anyway.

867
01:10:43,505 --> 01:10:45,735
BILLY:
Prisoner, step away from the fence.

868
01:10:47,710 --> 01:10:52,272
Civilian on the outside,
get back away from the fence.

869
01:10:53,182 --> 01:10:58,176
Civilian and prisoner, both of you,
step back away from the fence.

870
01:11:24,046 --> 01:11:25,513
NORRIS:
Hey.

871
01:11:25,748 --> 01:11:28,182
How's your brother adjusting
to being back?

872
01:11:28,617 --> 01:11:29,914
Uh, he's doing okay.

873
01:11:30,119 --> 01:11:32,883
- He's a hell of a guy.
- Yeah.

874
01:11:33,088 --> 01:11:35,921
Hey, I'm not talking about
the Silver Star or any of that.

875
01:11:36,125 --> 01:11:38,389
That day I picked him up,
we were driving back...

876
01:11:38,594 --> 01:11:41,495
...he never said a word about
what happened in that barbershop.

877
01:11:42,264 --> 01:11:44,095
What barbershop?

878
01:11:44,967 --> 01:11:48,266
Didn't even faze him enough
to bother mentioning it to you, huh?

879
01:11:49,204 --> 01:11:51,104
What are you talking about?

880
01:11:51,907 --> 01:11:53,602
Just a haircut.

881
01:11:54,943 --> 01:11:58,401
That's Ed Tully. He's a barber in town.

882
01:12:00,416 --> 01:12:04,352
Director Watson got permission
for us to go outside of camp.

883
01:12:04,586 --> 01:12:06,554
We are going to their park.

884
01:12:06,789 --> 01:12:09,280
Their home field. Ha-ha.

885
01:12:09,525 --> 01:12:11,152
That's great.

886
01:12:11,994 --> 01:12:14,292
Because that is the guy, Dad.

887
01:12:14,697 --> 01:12:17,996
That day in town? This was the guy.

888
01:12:20,703 --> 01:12:22,330
LYLE:
I have to be a part of this.

889
01:12:30,779 --> 01:12:33,111
KATIE: Mama?
SHIRLEY: Mm-hm?

890
01:12:33,449 --> 01:12:34,609
KATIE:
Um...

891
01:12:34,850 --> 01:12:35,976
[KATIE CLEARS THROAT]

892
01:12:36,218 --> 01:12:38,584
I've been accepted by a college.

893
01:12:38,787 --> 01:12:40,516
I'm gonna go.

894
01:12:43,959 --> 01:12:46,325
Katie. Okay.

895
01:12:48,530 --> 01:12:51,328
Delaware State University. What--?

896
01:12:51,633 --> 01:12:53,362
You wanna go to college in Delaware?

897
01:12:54,336 --> 01:12:58,295
What? College? You never talked
about anything like this before.

898
01:12:58,540 --> 01:13:01,600
I have money saved from my job.
I'll use that to pay for everything.

899
01:13:01,844 --> 01:13:03,835
You're not going.
You're staying in Abraham.

900
01:13:04,079 --> 01:13:06,343
When I get called up,
you're moving with us.

901
01:13:06,548 --> 01:13:08,516
- Billy.
KATIE: I've made up my mind.

902
01:13:08,751 --> 01:13:11,686
- I'm not asking for anything from you--
- You're staying with us.

903
01:13:11,887 --> 01:13:13,445
When we go to New York, we're all--

904
01:13:13,689 --> 01:13:16,351
I spent my life hearing about
how things are gonna change.

905
01:13:16,592 --> 01:13:19,220
- How we're gonna go to New York.
SHIRLEY: All right, Katie, just--

906
01:13:19,461 --> 01:13:22,021
No, Mama, no.
I don't wanna wait anymore for anything.

907
01:13:22,264 --> 01:13:24,528
I just wanna go.
I wanna do what I wanna do.

908
01:13:24,733 --> 01:13:26,564
BILLY:
You are not leaving home, Katie.

909
01:13:26,769 --> 01:13:28,566
You are not going off to school.

910
01:13:28,771 --> 01:13:30,363
You are not going back to that camp.

911
01:13:30,606 --> 01:13:33,507
- You are not seeing that Jap--
- He's not a Jap!

912
01:13:33,709 --> 01:13:34,641
[KATIE SCOFFS]

913
01:13:34,877 --> 01:13:37,812
You look at him and you see the people
who killed Billy Jr.

914
01:13:38,046 --> 01:13:41,277
Well, Lyle wasn't over there.
None of the people at those camps were.

915
01:13:41,483 --> 01:13:44,884
- We're not talking about that.
KATIE: What are we talking about, huh?

916
01:13:45,654 --> 01:13:47,588
All this time, talking about them.

917
01:13:47,790 --> 01:13:51,749
How they caused all this,
how they killed Billy.

918
01:13:52,361 --> 01:13:54,761
Why don't we talk about
what it really is?

919
01:13:54,997 --> 01:13:58,228
Why Billy Jr. was even there to begin with,
why he wasn't here at home.

920
01:13:58,434 --> 01:14:01,961
- Katie, that is enough.
- All those years trying to make him like you.

921
01:14:02,204 --> 01:14:04,331
Trying to make him be you.

922
01:14:04,573 --> 01:14:06,541
Forcing him to play baseball.

923
01:14:06,775 --> 01:14:09,403
Making him practice hours
and hours and hours.

924
01:14:09,645 --> 01:14:12,011
- He never wanted it.
BILLY: You don't know what he wanted.

925
01:14:12,214 --> 01:14:14,910
BILLY: You don't know anything about it.
- He hated it. He hated you!

926
01:14:15,117 --> 01:14:17,051
KATIE:
He couldn't stand being here anymore...

927
01:14:17,286 --> 01:14:19,481
...until finally he ran away to the Navy.

928
01:14:19,688 --> 01:14:22,486
That is why he was there.
That is why he was killed.

929
01:14:22,691 --> 01:14:24,750
It was you. You who killed him.

930
01:14:24,993 --> 01:14:27,325
- Shut up! Shut up!
SHIRLEY: Billy!

931
01:14:27,529 --> 01:14:29,019
- Shut up!
- Billy, no! No!

932
01:14:29,264 --> 01:14:32,199
[KATIE CRYING
AND SHIRLEY PANTING]

933
01:15:12,074 --> 01:15:14,508
LYLE: <i>My father had set up the game</i>
<i>with the Abraham team...</i>

934
01:15:14,743 --> 01:15:17,644
<i>...because he wanted us</i>
<i>to have a chance to prove ourselves...</i>

935
01:15:17,846 --> 01:15:19,643
<i>...to the people of the town.</i>

936
01:15:19,848 --> 01:15:23,375
<i>When I told him I had to be there...</i>

937
01:15:23,819 --> 01:15:27,653
<i>...he never brought up any of the things</i>
<i>that had happened between us in the past.</i>

938
01:15:27,856 --> 01:15:32,691
<i>All he said was,</i>
<i>"You'll have to work hard to be ready."</i>

939
01:15:52,648 --> 01:15:55,708
We're gonna challenge them
to a bet on the game, okay?

940
01:15:55,951 --> 01:15:57,418
All of us together.

941
01:15:57,653 --> 01:16:01,612
All it's gonna take is one quarter.
One quarter will do it.

942
01:16:01,857 --> 01:16:03,347
NORI:
Come on, give me a quarter.

943
01:16:03,592 --> 01:16:06,459
Look, one measly quarter,
that's all I need.

944
01:16:06,662 --> 01:16:08,562
NORI:
One measly quarter each. Okay?

945
01:16:08,764 --> 01:16:11,528
BAMBINO: Whoo! Sweet, kid.
NORI: Put your money on your team.

946
01:16:11,733 --> 01:16:13,633
BAMBINO: Give me another one.
Give me another one.

947
01:16:13,835 --> 01:16:15,803
Once again. Once again. Come on.

948
01:16:18,373 --> 01:16:22,673
NORI: One quarter, your bet.
Our bet on our team.

949
01:16:22,878 --> 01:16:25,369
All of us in one bet, together.
How's that?

950
01:16:26,114 --> 01:16:27,308
NORI:
Drop it on in.

951
01:16:27,950 --> 01:16:29,383
Attaboy.

952
01:16:29,585 --> 01:16:30,745
You got it.

953
01:16:30,986 --> 01:16:32,578
We're gonna get there.
Thank you very much.

954
01:16:32,821 --> 01:16:34,652
[BAMBINO GROANS]

955
01:16:48,403 --> 01:16:50,064
[CHATTERING]

956
01:17:08,924 --> 01:17:12,985
ANNOUNCER: Welcome to Skinner Field,
home of your Abraham Bees.

957
01:17:13,462 --> 01:17:15,157
We've got a special exhibition game...

958
01:17:15,397 --> 01:17:19,731
...between the Bees and a team
from the Topaz Relocation Camp.

959
01:17:21,637 --> 01:17:24,162
Quite a few people from the camp
came out to take a look.

960
01:17:24,406 --> 01:17:27,375
Probably the first time
they've ever seen a real game.

961
01:17:28,076 --> 01:17:31,170
A little birdie put it in my ear today
that Dapper Don Lemon...

962
01:17:31,413 --> 01:17:33,938
...the scout of the New York Yankees,
is coming by today.

963
01:17:34,182 --> 01:17:36,616
ANNOUNCER: Y'all know what happened
last time Don was here.

964
01:17:36,818 --> 01:17:38,115
Yep, that's right.

965
01:17:38,320 --> 01:17:40,379
Jimmy Hollister was called up
to the big club.

966
01:17:40,622 --> 01:17:41,782
Our Jimmy Hollister.

967
01:17:42,024 --> 01:17:46,188
We decided to treat this like any other day,
act like we didn't know he was coming.

968
01:17:46,962 --> 01:17:48,759
I heard he drives a big fancy car.

969
01:17:48,964 --> 01:17:51,762
A brand-new Roadmaster,
and he doesn't even like driving.

970
01:17:51,967 --> 01:17:53,400
[SHIRLEY CHUCKLES]

971
01:17:57,205 --> 01:17:59,765
- What the hell is this?
- Twenty-five hundred bucks.

972
01:18:00,008 --> 01:18:02,602
- What?
- Ten thousand quarters.

973
01:18:02,844 --> 01:18:04,937
Every person in camp is in on it.

974
01:18:05,180 --> 01:18:07,614
Twenty-five hundred dollars?
That's a new Cadillac.

975
01:18:08,016 --> 01:18:11,417
Yeah. We like to gamble.

976
01:18:12,220 --> 01:18:13,653
Billy.

977
01:18:13,889 --> 01:18:16,551
These are the guys that wanna put
money on the game.

978
01:18:16,792 --> 01:18:18,123
All right, how much? I'm in.

979
01:18:18,694 --> 01:18:21,128
Two thousand five hundred bucks.

980
01:18:21,329 --> 01:18:22,421
[ED SCOFFS]

981
01:18:22,664 --> 01:18:24,894
- What, $2000?
NORI: What?

982
01:18:25,300 --> 01:18:27,768
What's the matter, you scared?
Huh, you yellow?

983
01:18:28,003 --> 01:18:30,028
You don't even belong
on the same field as us.

984
01:18:30,272 --> 01:18:32,240
There's no way we can come up
with that much.

985
01:18:32,474 --> 01:18:34,203
And you guys are gonna back down?

986
01:18:34,409 --> 01:18:38,345
Come on, what have you got
that's worth 2500 that can cover the bet?

987
01:18:38,580 --> 01:18:41,105
Little slants just trying to show us
how rich they are.

988
01:18:44,453 --> 01:18:46,250
I have an idea.

989
01:18:47,956 --> 01:18:50,686
ANNOUNCER: This is a league game.
It was decided that a coin toss...

990
01:18:50,892 --> 01:18:55,352
- ...would determine which will bat first.
- Topaz, you will call the coin toss.

991
01:18:56,598 --> 01:18:57,997
Heads.

992
01:18:58,233 --> 01:18:59,165
Heads it is.

993
01:19:00,435 --> 01:19:01,834
We bat last.

994
01:19:02,037 --> 01:19:05,302
Topaz has elected to bat last.

995
01:19:05,741 --> 01:19:07,174
ANNOUNCER:
Looks like the Topaz team...

996
01:19:07,409 --> 01:19:10,310
...has decided to let the Bees
lead this thing off.

997
01:19:12,147 --> 01:19:13,944
KAZ:
Everybody...

998
01:19:15,317 --> 01:19:18,218
...we know what we have to do
to win today.

999
01:19:19,020 --> 01:19:20,351
But...

1000
01:19:20,555 --> 01:19:22,955
...today is not just about winning.

1001
01:19:24,459 --> 01:19:28,122
Today is about dignity.

1002
01:19:28,964 --> 01:19:33,367
Dignity of the game,
and the dignity we have...

1003
01:19:34,636 --> 01:19:36,069
...here.

1004
01:19:39,674 --> 01:19:41,198
Enough.

1005
01:19:41,810 --> 01:19:42,902
Let's play ball.

1006
01:19:43,712 --> 01:19:45,236
You heard him. Who are we?

1007
01:19:45,480 --> 01:19:46,469
- Topaz!
- Yellow!

1008
01:19:46,715 --> 01:19:48,205
Let's go, guys.

1009
01:19:49,885 --> 01:19:52,820
ANNOUNCER:
These guys are little, and I mean little.

1010
01:19:53,021 --> 01:19:55,546
It's almost like looking
at a bunch of midgets out there.

1011
01:19:55,791 --> 01:19:58,089
Personally, I always get a kick
out of midgets.

1012
01:19:58,293 --> 01:20:00,124
You see a midget, you gotta chuckle.

1013
01:20:00,328 --> 01:20:01,352
[CROWD LAUGHS]

1014
01:20:03,698 --> 01:20:07,930
Hey, your Abraham Bees leadoff hitter,
first baseman Ed Tully, steps up.

1015
01:20:08,136 --> 01:20:10,536
MAN 1: Come on, Ed.
MAN 2: Let's go, Ed.

1016
01:20:12,107 --> 01:20:14,041
[CROWD CHEERING]

1017
01:20:33,461 --> 01:20:36,225
Do that again. Throw at me.
Throw at me again. Come on.

1018
01:20:36,431 --> 01:20:39,366
ANNOUNCER: That had more
than "brush back" written on it.

1019
01:20:43,772 --> 01:20:45,933
The pitcher kid winds.

1020
01:20:47,375 --> 01:20:48,967
UMPIRE: Strike!
ED: What?

1021
01:20:49,211 --> 01:20:51,475
Attaboy, Lyle, attaboy.

1022
01:20:51,680 --> 01:20:53,807
Pitcher fella
has a decent-looking fastball.

1023
01:20:54,049 --> 01:20:54,981
UMPIRE:
Two!

1024
01:20:55,217 --> 01:20:57,344
ANNOUNCER:
There's a fastball right down the middle.

1025
01:20:59,321 --> 01:21:00,253
UMPIRE:
Out!

1026
01:21:00,488 --> 01:21:02,956
ANNOUNCER:
Strike three. He struck him out.

1027
01:21:04,359 --> 01:21:05,451
And that's one down.

1028
01:21:06,728 --> 01:21:10,061
Next up, we've got catcher Billy Burrell.

1029
01:21:10,265 --> 01:21:14,531
We're all expecting Billy to be called up.
No one deserves it more than him.

1030
01:21:15,670 --> 01:21:18,104
I've never known a player
who respected the game more.

1031
01:21:18,306 --> 01:21:20,365
MAN 3: Mash it, Billy.
MAN 4: Go, Billy!

1032
01:21:20,775 --> 01:21:24,575
ANNOUNCER: My hat's off to Billy.
I couldn't be happier for him.

1033
01:21:28,750 --> 01:21:30,547
UMPIRE: Strike!
BILLY: Come on, that's outside.

1034
01:21:30,752 --> 01:21:32,652
[NORI WHISTLES]

1035
01:21:32,854 --> 01:21:36,290
Hey, it's a little different when you both
have to play fair now, huh?

1036
01:21:37,125 --> 01:21:41,061
Just a little bit. Just a little bit.

1037
01:21:41,897 --> 01:21:44,058
This time, it's straight up.

1038
01:21:45,233 --> 01:21:47,064
WOMAN: Come on.
BOY: Let's go, Burrell!

1039
01:21:47,269 --> 01:21:48,702
Straight up.

1040
01:22:00,849 --> 01:22:02,783
[CROWD CHEERING]

1041
01:22:03,018 --> 01:22:05,316
ANNOUNCER:
Down the line, hooking...

1042
01:22:05,520 --> 01:22:07,488
ANNOUNCER: Foul.
UMPIRE: Foul ball!

1043
01:22:07,722 --> 01:22:09,155
UMPIRE: Okay.
MAN 4: Come on, Billy.

1044
01:22:16,498 --> 01:22:17,863
UMPIRE:
You're out!

1045
01:22:18,066 --> 01:22:19,693
NORI:
Beautiful, beautiful.

1046
01:22:19,935 --> 01:22:21,994
That's the way to do it, now.
That's the way.

1047
01:22:25,173 --> 01:22:27,437
ANNOUNCER: These guys have never seen
anything like Grover.

1048
01:22:27,642 --> 01:22:29,473
Grover really had a shot
a few years back.

1049
01:22:29,678 --> 01:22:32,579
He told me that Don Lemon himself
came to take a look at him.

1050
01:22:32,781 --> 01:22:35,682
Talked to him about
working on his curve ball.

1051
01:22:35,884 --> 01:22:37,010
Coming to the plate...

1052
01:22:37,252 --> 01:22:41,848
...this must be, let's see, Takeshita.

1053
01:22:43,892 --> 01:22:45,757
UMPIRE:
Ball one.

1054
01:22:51,499 --> 01:22:53,126
UMPIRE:
Strike one.

1055
01:22:53,501 --> 01:22:55,594
UMPIRE: Strike two.
ANNOUNCER: Grover winds.

1056
01:22:55,837 --> 01:22:58,772
UMPIRE: You're out!
- And down he goes.

1057
01:22:59,474 --> 01:23:02,307
ANNOUNCER: As next batter,
this pitcher kid's coming up.

1058
01:23:02,811 --> 01:23:04,608
Come on, Grover, come on.

1059
01:23:07,549 --> 01:23:09,847
ANNOUNCER:
A little tap down the line.

1060
01:23:10,819 --> 01:23:12,753
That's two down.

1061
01:23:13,188 --> 01:23:17,215
Let's forget about this exhibition game.
Teach these guys a real lesson.

1062
01:23:18,126 --> 01:23:20,754
ANNOUNCER: This big fella, I don't know
what he's doing with them.

1063
01:23:20,996 --> 01:23:22,463
He looks colored to me.

1064
01:23:22,697 --> 01:23:25,598
ANNOUNCER: I guess he's married to one
of them, or got some of their blood.

1065
01:23:25,800 --> 01:23:29,236
Scorecard says he calls himself Bambino.

1066
01:23:29,471 --> 01:23:31,336
Got no comment on that.

1067
01:23:33,708 --> 01:23:34,675
Grover winds and...

1068
01:23:35,643 --> 01:23:36,803
Oh, hey.

1069
01:23:37,045 --> 01:23:40,310
They don't have fastballs like that
where they come from.

1070
01:23:40,782 --> 01:23:44,240
First inning: one, two, three.
Here comes the pitch.

1071
01:23:44,486 --> 01:23:45,783
UMPIRE: Strike!
ANNOUNCER: Down he goes.

1072
01:23:45,987 --> 01:23:47,249
ANNOUNCER: Grab some pine.
UMPIRE: Out!

1073
01:23:47,455 --> 01:23:48,615
ANNOUNCER: Take your seat.
UMPIRE: Out!

1074
01:23:48,857 --> 01:23:52,258
ANNOUNCER: Grover's working a no-hitter.
It's damn near impossible to tell them apart.

1075
01:23:52,460 --> 01:23:54,724
Top of the fourth, and Nomura--
Nom-- Nom-- Nom--

1076
01:23:54,929 --> 01:23:56,863
Whatever-his-name-is delivers, and--

1077
01:24:02,037 --> 01:24:06,303
ANNOUNCER: They don't have any bats,
but their defense is looking good out there.

1078
01:24:08,276 --> 01:24:10,039
Where is he?

1079
01:24:10,378 --> 01:24:13,245
JOE: Do you want me to go look around
and see if anyone's seen him?

1080
01:24:13,782 --> 01:24:15,647
Oh, would you, Joe? I'd appreciate that.

1081
01:24:15,850 --> 01:24:18,410
ANNOUNCER: This Topaz kid, now,
I don't know if he's throwing...

1082
01:24:18,653 --> 01:24:20,587
...some special
imported pitches or what...

1083
01:24:20,822 --> 01:24:22,983
...but he's got himself a shutout
going as well.

1084
01:24:24,926 --> 01:24:27,895
UMPIRE: Strike three. You're out.
NORI: We call that his radio ball.

1085
01:24:28,129 --> 01:24:32,532
You heard it, but didn't see it.
Did you, sergeant-san?

1086
01:24:33,368 --> 01:24:34,767
[NORI CACKLES]

1087
01:24:36,938 --> 01:24:38,337
ANNOUNCER:
Grover winds and...

1088
01:24:39,040 --> 01:24:40,166
[CROWD CHEERING]

1089
01:24:40,408 --> 01:24:42,069
Bambino, I love you!

1090
01:24:42,310 --> 01:24:46,076
NORI: Yeah, Bambino!
ANNOUNCER: My, oh, my, see it fly.

1091
01:24:51,152 --> 01:24:54,212
ANNOUNCER:
The Topaz team goes up, 1 -0.

1092
01:24:54,889 --> 01:24:58,689
Go! Yeah! Yeah!

1093
01:24:59,894 --> 01:25:03,193
That calls for a little liquid refreshment.

1094
01:25:08,570 --> 01:25:10,936
JOE: He's here.
- Oh, ha-ha-ha.

1095
01:25:11,139 --> 01:25:12,071
Thank God.

1096
01:25:14,008 --> 01:25:15,873
SHIRLEY:
Billy, he's here.

1097
01:25:16,077 --> 01:25:17,669
- He just got here.
- What?

1098
01:25:17,912 --> 01:25:21,313
He always reserves a seat when he comes,
and Joe just went to find out where he is.

1099
01:25:21,516 --> 01:25:22,744
Oh...

1100
01:25:22,951 --> 01:25:24,919
- New York Yankees.
- New York Yankees.

1101
01:25:25,153 --> 01:25:26,484
[SHIRLEY LAUGHS]

1102
01:25:29,090 --> 01:25:31,217
ANNOUNCER:
Ladies and gentlemen, please rise...

1103
01:25:31,459 --> 01:25:33,586
...for the seventh-inning stretch.

1104
01:25:33,828 --> 01:25:37,229
Feel like you could use a haircut?
Don't forget about Ed's Barbershop.

1105
01:25:37,599 --> 01:25:40,466
Cut it right, cut it at Ed's.

1106
01:25:42,303 --> 01:25:46,239
And join me in singing
"Take Me Out to the Ball Game."

1107
01:25:46,474 --> 01:25:51,411
[ANNOUNCER & CROWD SINGING
"TAKE ME OUT TO THE BALL GAME"]

1108
01:25:56,718 --> 01:25:58,845
I bought my bus ticket.

1109
01:25:59,220 --> 01:26:01,814
I leave for Delaware day after tomorrow.

1110
01:26:04,692 --> 01:26:07,058
That's great, Katie.

1111
01:26:08,329 --> 01:26:11,162
I won't go if you don't want me to.

1112
01:26:15,770 --> 01:26:17,260
No.

1113
01:26:18,306 --> 01:26:20,866
No, I want you to, I do.

1114
01:26:21,109 --> 01:26:23,976
- Really?
- Yeah, really.

1115
01:26:24,512 --> 01:26:28,004
Oh, God. I'm so scared, Lyle.
I have never been anywhere by myself.

1116
01:26:28,249 --> 01:26:30,683
Yeah, I know.
It's nothing to be afraid of, all right?

1117
01:26:30,885 --> 01:26:32,477
You're gonna be fine.

1118
01:26:32,720 --> 01:26:36,952
I just keep thinking about maybe next year,
maybe you could come, you could join me.

1119
01:26:37,158 --> 01:26:38,955
We could be in Delaware...

1120
01:26:39,160 --> 01:26:40,889
[SHIRLEY LAUGHING]

1121
01:26:45,667 --> 01:26:47,100
[KATIE CLEARS THROAT]

1122
01:26:47,302 --> 01:26:49,463
Mom, this is Lyle.

1123
01:26:49,904 --> 01:26:50,962
This is my mom.

1124
01:26:53,174 --> 01:26:54,835
LYLE:
Hello, Mrs. Burrell.

1125
01:26:55,476 --> 01:26:57,706
It's a pleasure to meet you.

1126
01:26:59,080 --> 01:27:01,344
It's nice to meet you.

1127
01:27:08,089 --> 01:27:09,681
Mom, Dad.

1128
01:27:13,928 --> 01:27:15,225
This is Katie.

1129
01:27:15,430 --> 01:27:16,419
Hello.

1130
01:27:16,664 --> 01:27:18,723
And her mother and father.

1131
01:28:00,074 --> 01:28:02,201
ANNOUNCER:
Well, here we are in the top of the ninth...

1132
01:28:02,443 --> 01:28:04,206
...and our Bees are trailing, 1 -0.

1133
01:28:04,412 --> 01:28:08,348
One on, two outs, and now we got
Ed Tully coming up.

1134
01:28:11,286 --> 01:28:13,345
Ed hits a slow dribble
off the first-base line.

1135
01:28:13,588 --> 01:28:14,555
[GRUNTING]

1136
01:28:14,789 --> 01:28:15,778
Look out.

1137
01:28:16,658 --> 01:28:18,091
BAMBINO:
Whoa. Whoa, whoa.

1138
01:28:18,293 --> 01:28:19,726
What, you wanna hit somebody?

1139
01:28:19,961 --> 01:28:22,930
Come hit me. Come hit me, man.
You wanna hit somebody?

1140
01:28:23,431 --> 01:28:26,525
UMPIRE:
Hey, catcher, get back behind the plate.

1141
01:28:27,502 --> 01:28:29,993
ANNOUNCER:
That's Ed Tully style baseball.

1142
01:28:30,238 --> 01:28:31,637
MAN 1:
Stay on the base, Ed.

1143
01:28:31,839 --> 01:28:33,272
[CROWD APPLAUDING]

1144
01:28:33,508 --> 01:28:36,375
Next up, we got catcher Billy Burrell.

1145
01:28:36,577 --> 01:28:39,205
ANNOUNCER:
Nomura's made Billy look bad today.

1146
01:28:39,447 --> 01:28:41,472
Struck him out three times.

1147
01:28:41,949 --> 01:28:45,885
I can tell you right now, Billy does not
wanna strike out to end this game.

1148
01:28:49,691 --> 01:28:50,680
MAN 2:
Go Burrell!

1149
01:28:50,925 --> 01:28:53,155
ANNOUNCER:
Two on, two outs.

1150
01:28:53,361 --> 01:28:55,591
This game is on the line right here, folks.

1151
01:28:57,498 --> 01:28:59,932
MAN 3:
Knock it out of the park, Burrell!

1152
01:29:14,949 --> 01:29:16,610
[CROWD CHEERING]

1153
01:29:20,788 --> 01:29:21,812
ANNOUNCER:
Bombs away!

1154
01:29:23,157 --> 01:29:25,284
Billy just hit a three-run homer.

1155
01:29:25,526 --> 01:29:28,927
It doesn't get any better than this, fans.

1156
01:29:45,780 --> 01:29:47,839
I'm sorry, sugar. I'm really sorry.

1157
01:29:48,082 --> 01:29:49,709
SHIRLEY:
What is it, Joe? What's the matter?

1158
01:29:49,951 --> 01:29:52,681
JOE: I found out where Don Lemon
reserved his seat.

1159
01:29:52,920 --> 01:29:54,785
Right over there.

1160
01:29:55,590 --> 01:29:57,558
JOE:
I made a mistake.

1161
01:29:58,993 --> 01:30:01,427
Don Lemon isn't here.

1162
01:30:33,928 --> 01:30:36,795
That's a game winner, Billy Burrell!

1163
01:30:36,998 --> 01:30:38,590
SHIRLEY:
That's a winner!

1164
01:30:38,833 --> 01:30:41,427
ANNOUNCER: One swing of the bat
and your Abraham Bees...

1165
01:30:41,669 --> 01:30:44,263
...have taken control of this game.

1166
01:30:46,374 --> 01:30:49,468
We can just about call it a day here.

1167
01:30:52,146 --> 01:30:53,977
Hey, everybody.

1168
01:30:54,649 --> 01:30:57,777
KAZ: I don't wanna see any heads
hanging down.

1169
01:31:00,455 --> 01:31:02,685
Every one of you.

1170
01:31:08,663 --> 01:31:10,961
I am proud of you.

1171
01:31:14,602 --> 01:31:16,229
BAMBINO: We're all here, yeah?
PLAYER: Yeah.

1172
01:31:16,471 --> 01:31:18,132
BAMBINO: We're all here, yeah?
PLAYERS: Yeah.

1173
01:31:18,372 --> 01:31:20,169
Let's give them something
to cheer about, guys.

1174
01:31:20,374 --> 01:31:21,432
- Who are we?
- Topaz.

1175
01:31:21,676 --> 01:31:22,608
- Who are we?
- Topaz.

1176
01:31:22,844 --> 01:31:23,970
Let's go, let's go!

1177
01:31:24,212 --> 01:31:26,203
Well, here we are. Bottom of the ninth.

1178
01:31:26,447 --> 01:31:29,814
Your Abraham Bees 3, Topaz 1.

1179
01:31:30,017 --> 01:31:32,611
All right, let's get this thing over with.
Three and out.

1180
